'''Richard Dwight "Richie" Farmer''' (born August 25, 1969) is an American former collegiate basketball player and [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] politician from the [[U.S. state]] of [[Kentucky]]. He served as the Kentucky Agriculture Commissioner from 2004 to 2012 and was the running mate of [[David L. Williams (politician)|David L. Williams]] in the [[Kentucky gubernatorial election, 2011|2011 gubernatorial election]]. After leaving office, Farmer was investigated for violating state campaign finance laws and misappropriating state resources and was sentenced to 27 months in federal prison along with a concurrent 12 months in state prison.

A [[point guard]], Farmer led [[Clay County High School]] to the 1987 [[Sweet Sixteen (KHSAA State Basketball Championship)|Kentucky High School Athletic Association (KHSAA) State Basketball Championship]] and, in 1988, was named [[Kentucky Mr. Basketball]] and Kentucky Associated Press Male High School Athlete of the Year after setting a championship game record with 51 points in a losing effort. Although he was popular state-wide and publicly stated his desire to play collegiate basketball for the [[Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball|Kentucky Wildcats]], Coach [[Eddie Sutton]] was reluctant to offer Farmer a scholarship. After Farmer announced that he would visit other colleges and issued a deadline past which he would no longer consider Kentucky without a scholarship offer, Sutton relented and Farmer joined the [[University of Kentucky]].

Kentucky struggled during Farmer's freshman year, finishing with a 13<U+2013>19 record, and by mid-season, fans were accusing Sutton of unfairly favoring his son, [[Sean Sutton|Sean]], over Farmer at the point guard position. Sutton resigned in the offseason due to a pay-for-play scandal for which the [[NCAA]] banned Kentucky from postseason play for two years. Sutton's replacement, [[Rick Pitino]], instituted a rigorous conditioning program and fast-paced style of play that improved Farmer's performance. After spending his junior season as a backup to [[Sean Woods]], Farmer transitioned to [[shooting guard]] and became a starter in the middle of his senior year. Again eligible for postseason competition, the Wildcats won the [[Southeastern Conference]] tournament and reached the Regional Finals of the [[1992 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|1992 NCAA Tournament]], losing in overtime on a last-second shot by [[Duke Blue Devils men's basketball|Duke]]'s [[Christian Laettner]] in [[The Shot (Duke<U+2013>Kentucky)|a game]] regarded by many as the greatest college basketball game ever played. The team's seniors &ndash; Farmer, Woods, [[John Pelphrey]], and [[Deron Feldhaus]] &ndash; were dubbed "The Unforgettables", and their jerseys were hung from the rafters of [[Rupp Arena]] following the [[1991<U+2013>92 Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball team|1991&ndash;92 season]].

Farmer parlayed his status as a basketball icon into two terms as Kentucky Agriculture Commissioner from 2004 to 2012, winning both elections by large margins. In 2011, [[President of the Kentucky Senate|Kentucky Senate President]] David L. Williams tapped Farmer &ndash; considered a rising star in the state Republican Party &ndash; as his running mate in the gubernatorial election. They were defeated by Democratic Governor [[Steve Beshear]] and his running mate [[Jerry Abramson]]. During the campaign, media reports alleged that Farmer had misused state funds and property as agriculture commissioner and Farmer's successor collaborated with the state auditor to investigate the allegations. As a result, the Executive Branch Ethics Commission charged Farmer with 42 ethics violations &ndash; the most against an individual in state history. [[Attorney General of Kentucky|Attorney General]] [[Jack Conway (politician)|Jack Conway]] also charged Farmer with violating state [[Campaign finance in the United States|campaign finance laws]], and a federal [[grand jury]] followed with five [[indictment]]s for abuses of power. Farmer initially contested the charges, but later agreed to a [[plea bargain]]. On January 14, 2014, Farmer was sentenced to 27 months in federal prison and ordered to pay $120,500 in [[restitution]] and $65,000 in fines. As of 2015, he is an inmate at a satellite camp of the [[United States Penitentiary, Hazelton]] near [[Bruceton Mills, West Virginia]].

==Early life==
Richard Dwight ("Richie") Farmer, Jr. was born on August 25, 1969, in [[Corbin, Kentucky]], but grew up in the [[eastern Kentucky]] town of [[Manchester, Kentucky|Manchester]].<ref name=winhabit>{{cite news |last=Maloney |first=Mark |title=Winning is Habit for Clay's Farmer |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=December 16, 1986 |page=C8}}</ref><ref name=offcharts>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Emotionally 'Off the Charts' |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 7, 1992 |page=D10}}</ref> He was the second of three children born to Richard and Virginia Farmer.<ref name=proud>{{cite news |last=Brammer |first=Jack |title=Farmer Takes Pride in Defying the Skeptics &ndash; Trying Year Marked by Unflattering Publicity |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=October 19, 2011 |page=A1}}</ref> Because of his physical maturity &ndash; he reportedly began shaving at age 12 and had begun wearing his trademark mustache by his [[Eleventh grade|junior year]] in high school &ndash; Farmer was frequently questioned about his age.<ref name=winhabit /><ref name=8thgrade /> The {{height|ft=5|in=11|adj=on}} left-hander's [[vertical leap]] measured {{convert|40|in|cm}} in high school.<ref name=winhabit /> He credited his father, a transportation manager at a local coal mine and a standout [[point guard]] at [[Clay County High School]] in 1963, with developing his basketball acumen.<ref name=winhabit />

As an [[eighth grade]]r, Farmer played basketball for his grade school basketball team, as well as the freshman, junior varsity, and varsity teams at Clay County High School.<ref name=winner>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Farmer Just Wants Fans to Remember Him as a Winner |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 5, 1992 |page=C1}}</ref> He played sparingly during the varsity team's regular season but received 68 seconds of playing time &ndash; scoring 2 points &ndash; during the Tigers' victory over [[Owensboro High School]] in the 1984 [[Sweet Sixteen (KHSAA State Basketball Championship)|Kentucky High School Athletic Association (KHSAA) State Basketball Championship]].<ref name=winhabit /><ref name=8thgrade>{{cite news |last=Fields |first=Mike |title=It's 'Another Day at the Office' for Freshman as Clay Advances |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 23, 1985 |page=D1}}</ref> He also played [[American football|football]] on a team that won the county championship that year.<ref name=winhabit /> He eventually stopped playing football, but continued to play [[baseball]] &ndash; as a [[pitcher]] and [[first baseman]] &ndash; in addition to basketball until his senior year of high school.<ref name=winhabit /><ref name=appoy>{{cite news |last=Fields |first=Mike |title=Kentucky Destined to be Second-Best in All-Star Rivalry |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=June 24, 1988 |page=D3}}</ref>

==High school basketball==
===Freshman and sophomore===
As a freshman, Farmer led his team in scoring during the regular season, averaging 16.4 points per game from the [[shooting guard]] position.<ref name=winhabit /><ref name=freshmanstarter>{{cite news |last=Fields |first=Mike |title=Hillbrook Classic Visitors Have Won 19, Lost 0 |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=December 14, 1984 |page=C1}}</ref> He also led the Tigers in scoring in each of their three games ''en route'' to the 13th Region [[Kentucky High School Athletic Association]] basketball championship.<ref name=freshmanseason>{{cite news |last=Fields |first=Mike |title=Boone and Clay Similar on Court, but Not in History |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 20, 1985 |page=C1}}</ref> In the opening round of the 1985 KHSAA state tournament, Farmer scored 14 points on 6 of 16 shooting in a win over [[Boone County High School]].<ref name=8thgrade /> Then, in back-to-back victories against [[Metcalfe County High School]] and [[Doss High School]], he led his team with 21 and 20 points, respectively, to help Clay County reach the tournament finals.<ref name=8thgrade /><ref name=1985semis>{{cite news |last=Fields |first=Mike |title=Clay County, Hopkinsville Take Dissimilar Routes to Finals |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 24, 1985 |page=C6}}</ref> Farmer scored 10 points in Clay County's 65&ndash;64 loss to [[Hopkinsville High School]] in the championship game.<ref name=1985finals>{{cite news |last=Fields |first=Mike |title=Hopkinsville Wins 65-64 Over Clay for State Crown |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 24, 1985 |page=C1}}</ref> He was the tournament's second-highest scorer with 69 points, one behind Hopkinsville's Lamont Ware, and finished second in the voting for the tournament's Most Valuable Player, which went to Hopkinsville's Wendell Quarles.<ref name=1985high>{{cite news |last=McGill |first=John |title=UK Skipped First NCAA Tourney |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 29, 1985 |page=C2}}</ref><ref name=1986opener>{{cite news |last=Fields |first=Mike |title=Round I of Clay-Pulaski Went into OT, so Expect a Thriller |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 19, 1986 |page=10}}</ref> Only [[Apollo High School (Kentucky)|Apollo High School]]'s [[Rex Chapman]] received more votes for the all-tournament team.<ref name=winhabit />

Clay County ranked only behind Owensboro and [[Scott County High School]] in the ''[[Lexington Herald-Leader]]'''s 1985&ndash;86 preseason coaches poll.<ref name=1986preseason>{{cite news |last=Fields |first=Mike |title=Scott County Coach Says It's Lovely at the Top |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=November 22, 1985 |page=C1}}</ref> During Clay County's 22&ndash;6 regular season, Farmer, who moved to the point guard position, averaged 18.6 points, 10 assists, and 8 rebounds per game.<ref name=winhabit /> The Tigers won the 13th District Title, setting up a matchup with [[Pulaski County High School (Kentucky)|Pulaski County High School]] in the first round of the KSHAA state tournament.<ref name=1986opener /> Farmer had scored 30 points in Clay County's regular season matchup with Pulaski County, but his team lost by one point in overtime.<ref name=1986loss /> In the tournament rematch, Pulaski County held Farmer to 20 points and won 83&ndash;78; Coach Dave Fraley credited a defense centered around stopping Farmer for his team's victory.<ref name=1986loss>{{cite news |last=McLean |first=Gene |title=Coach's Kid Leads Pulaski to 2nd Round; Fraley has 26 Points as Maroons Overcome Clay County 83-78 |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 20, 1986 |page=D1}}</ref>

===Junior===
In the ''Lexington Herald-Leader'''s 1986&ndash;87 preseason coaches' poll, Clay County was ranked 14th in the state, and Farmer was named one of the state's best 25 players.<ref name=1987preseason>{{cite news |last=Fields |first=Mike |title=Hopkinsville Rates as Team to Beat |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=November 27, 1986 |page=C1}}</ref><ref name=1987top25>{{cite news |last=Fields |first=Mike |title=Despite His Size, Hopkinsville's Ware has Climbed to Top |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=November 27, 1986 |page=C1}}</ref> Farmer led his team in scoring at 23.9 points per game, and Clay County finished the regular season with a record of 28&ndash;2 and again won the 13th Region tournament.<ref name=futureisnow>{{cite news |last=Fields |first=Mike |title=For Clay County, Future is Now Against Highlands |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 25, 1987 |page=15}}</ref><ref name=1987season>{{cite news |title=Rowan Shocks Boyd 61-48 |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 18, 1987 |page=D3}}</ref> Farmer scored 19 points and grabbed 5 rebounds in his team's 90&ndash;80 victory over [[Highlands High School (Fort Thomas, Kentucky)|Highlands High School]] in the KHSAA state tournament's opening round, but his performance was overshadowed by teammate Russell Chadwell's 43 points.<ref name=1987opener>{{cite news |last=Fields |first=Mike |title=Chadwell's 43 Push Clay Past Highlands |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 27, 1987 |page=E2}}</ref> In the quarterfinals, Farmer led the Tigers with 19 points, defeating [[LaRue County High School]] 62&ndash;56 in front of 24,041 spectators at [[Lexington, Kentucky|Lexington]]'s [[Rupp Arena]], a record crowd for a high school basketball game.<ref name=1987quarters>{{cite news |last=Fields |first=Mike |title=Clay Holds Off LaRue 62&ndash;56 as Record 24,041 Look On |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 28, 1987 |page=D6}}</ref> In the first half of Clay County's semifinal matchup with [[Madison Central High School (Kentucky)|Madison Central High School]], Farmer scored 18 and his younger brother, Russ, added 12 to account for 30 of their team's 39 first-half points.<ref name=1987semis>{{cite news |last=Fields |first=Mike |title=Farmer Brothers Lead Clay Past Madison Central |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 29, 1987 |page=C8}}</ref> The Tigers' 17-point halftime lead grew to as many as 25 in the second half, and the elder Farmer again led his team with 24 total points in Clay County's 78&ndash;58 victory.<ref name=1987semis />

The win over Madison Central set up a title game between Clay County and [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]]'s [[Ballard High School (Louisville, Kentucky)|Ballard High School]].<ref name=longonheart>{{cite news |last=Maloney |first=Mark |title=Long on Heart, Clay Takes Crown Over Ballard in OT |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 29, 1987 |page=C1}}</ref> Clay County had only one starter taller than {{convert|6|ft|m}}, while Ballard started four players taller than {{height|ft=6|in=3}}, including star shooting guard [[Allan Houston]].<ref name=longonheart /> The game featured 24 ties and 15 lead changes; neither team led by more than four points during regulation.<ref name=longonheart /> Farmer scored Clay County's last 9 points in regulation, including consecutive go-ahead baskets at 3:19, 2:46, and 0:30.<ref name=1987mvp>{{cite news |last=Clay |first=John |title=MVP Richie Farmer Proud Mountains Own Title Again |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 29, 1987 |page=C14}}</ref> Ballard's Leonard Taylor scored on a put-back basket at the buzzer to tie the score at 65 and force overtime.<ref name=longonheart /> Clay County never trailed in the overtime, and Farmer's {{convert|15|ft|m|adj=on}} [[Jump shot (basketball)|jump shot]] with 1:44 left put the Tigers in the lead for good.<ref name=longonheart /> The 76&ndash;73 win was Clay County's first-ever KHSAA state championship.<ref name=longonheart /> Farmer played all 35 minutes of the game and led all scorers with 27 points to go with 6 rebounds and 4 assists.<ref name=longonheart /><ref name=1987finals>{{cite news |last=Maloney |first=Mark |title=Richie Farmer's 27 Help Clay Take Title Over Ballard in OT |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 29, 1987 |page=C1}}</ref> He was named to the all-tournament team, selected the tournament's Most Valuable Player, and given the Ted Sanford Award for citizenship, basketball ability, academic achievement, and sportsmanship.<ref name=1987mvp /> He was also the only underclassman named to the ''Lexington Herald-Leader'''s 1987 All-State First Team.<ref name=1987allstate>{{cite news |last=Fileds |first=Mike |title=Pelphrey Named Mr. Basketball, Tops All-State Team Feldhaus, Ellery Close Behind |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=April 5, 1987 |page=C1}}</ref>

In the summer following his junior year, Farmer was named to the Kentucky Junior All-Star Team, which played exhibition games throughout Europe, including stops in [[Iceland]], the [[Netherlands]], and [[West Germany]].<ref name=littlerest>{{cite news |last=Cox |first=Earl |title=Clay County's Farmer Has Gotten Little Rest This Summer |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=July 3, 1987 |page=D8}}</ref> After the European trip, he helped lead Clay County to a 15&ndash;0 record in [[Amateur Athletic Union]] play.<ref name=littlerest /> It was the first AAU season which recognized the [[three-point field goal]], and Farmer made 53 of his 73 three-point attempts.<ref name=glow>{{cite news |last=Fields |first=Mike |title=All-Stars Giving Prep Football a Healthy Glow |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=July 17, 1987 |page=D7}}</ref> In July 1987, the Kentucky Junior All-Stars finished second to a team from [[South Carolina]] in the Kentucky Prep All-Star Festival at [[Memorial Coliseum (University of Kentucky)|Memorial Coliseum]] in Lexington; Farmer sat out the championship game with a hand injury he suffered in the previous game.<ref name=kpasf>{{cite news |title=Kentucky Falls in Prep Finals |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=July 6, 1987 |page=C3}}</ref>

===Senior===
Clay County was ranked as the top team in the state in the 1987&ndash;88 preseason coaches' poll, and Farmer was voted the state's best prep prospect, garnering twice as many votes as second-place prospect Allan Houston.<ref name=stillking>{{cite news |last=Fields |first=Mike |title=Clay's Still King, Ready to Seek Another Crown  |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=December 1, 1987 |page=C1}}</ref><ref name=biggame>{{cite news |last=Fields |first=Mike |title=Farmer is Hunting Big Game Once Again |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=December 1, 1987 |page=C1}}</ref> The Tigers started the year 8&ndash;0 before suffering their only regular season loss in the first game of the 1987 [[Beach Ball Classic]] against [[Eau Claire High School (South Carolina)|Eau Claire High School]].<ref name=clayrecord>{{cite news |title=Richie Farmer Breaks Clay's Scoring Record |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=December 29, 1987 |page=C5}}</ref> In Clay County's next game in the Classic, Farmer broke the school's career scoring record, scoring his 2,193rd point in a 76&ndash;57 win over [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]]'s [[Nathan Hale High School (Oklahoma)|Nathan Hale High School]].<ref name=clayrecord /> Gary Gregory, who had held the record since 1974, was in attendance at the game.<ref name=clayrecord /> In the tournament's fifth place game, Farmer scored 33 points and broke the single-game record for assists with 16, besting [[Kenny Anderson (basketball)|Kenny Anderson]]'s year-old record of 13.<ref name=beachball>{{cite news |title=Clay Claims Fifth Place With Win Over Simi Valley |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=December 31, 1987 |page=C3}}</ref> Clay County defeated [[Simi Valley High School]] 95&ndash;91, and Farmer was selected as the tournament's Outstanding Player and named to the all-tournament team.<ref name=beachball />

In the opening round of the January 1988 [[Louisville Invitational Tournament]] (LIT), Farmer scored 40 points on 15 of 30 shooting in a 86&ndash;82 win over [[Pleasure Ridge Park High School]], pushing Clay County's record to 16&ndash;1 and setting up another meeting with Allan Houston's Ballard team.<ref name=litopener>{{cite news |last=Fields |first=Mike |title=Clay, Ballard Need Rallies to Advance to LIT Showdown |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=January 23, 1988 |page=D4}}</ref> Farmer scored 39 points &ndash; including 14 of his 15 free throws &ndash; and grabbed 12 rebounds in Clay County's 92&ndash;88 double overtime victory.<ref name=litsemis>{{cite news |last=Fields |first=Mike |title=Rematch Ends After 2 OTs as Clay Outlasts Ballard 92-88 in Semifinal |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=January 24, 1988 |page=C12}}</ref> In the championship game against [[Bardstown High School]], Farmer battled through fatigue and a thigh injury to lead his team in scoring with 24 points in an overtime win.<ref name=litfinals>{{cite news |last=Fields |first=Mike |title=Clay Beats Bardstown in Overtime for LIT Title |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=January 24, 1988 |page=C1}}</ref> In the three-game tournament, Farmer scored 103 points and played all of his team's 105 minutes, while committing only 4 [[Turnover (basketball)|turnovers]].<ref name=litfinals /><ref name=chance>{{cite news |last=Fields |first=Mike |title=Clay's Farmer Deserves Chance to Play for UK |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=January 26, 1988 |page=C1}}</ref> He was selected to the all-tournament team and named tournament MVP.<ref name=litfinals /> Already being recruited by [[WKU Hilltoppers men's basketball|Western Kentucky]], [[Alabama Crimson Tide men's basketball|Alabama]], and [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish men's basketball|Notre Dame]], Farmer's performances in the Beach Ball Classic and LIT brought notice from [[Eastern Kentucky Colonels men's basketball|Eastern Kentucky]], [[Wake Forest Demon Deacons men's basketball|Wake Forest]], [[Auburn Tigers men's basketball|Auburn]], [[Louisville Cardinals men's basketball|Louisville]], and [[Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball|Kentucky]].<ref name=chance />

In the 49th District Championship game, Farmer broke Clay County's single-game scoring record with 51 points in a 101&ndash;59 win over [[Jackson County High School]].<ref name=gamerecord>{{cite news |title=Farmer Scores 51 as Clay Captures Title Middlesboro Outduels Bell in 4 OTs |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 5, 1988 |page=D5}}</ref> In the 13th Region tournament opener, Farmer scored 40 points as Clay County defeated [[Corbin High School]] 75&ndash;56.<ref name=1988regionalopener>{{cite news |title=Farmer's 40 Lead Clay Past Corbin |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 9, 1988 |page=B6}}</ref> Clay County went on to defeat [[Bell County High School]] 53&ndash;36 in the semifinals and [[Knox Central High School]] 73&ndash;69 in the finals to once again advance to the KHSAA state tournament.<ref name=1988regionalsemis>{{cite news |title=Hart Stuns Bardstown 96&ndash;92 in 5th Region Semis |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 12, 1988 |page=D6}}</ref><ref name=1988regionalfinals>{{cite news |last=Fields |first=Mike |title=Rowan is Taking Its Date with Clay County in Stride |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 16, 1988 |page=D11}}</ref> Farmer scored 38 points on 14 of 24 shooting in a victory over [[Rowan County High School]] in the tournament's opening round.<ref name=1988opener>{{cite news |last=Maloney |first=Mark |title=Richie Farmer's 38 Lead the Way as Clay Rolls On |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 18, 1988 |page=D1}}</ref> Four minutes into the Tigers' quarterfinal matchup against LaRue County High School, Farmer scored a three-point basket that tied [[Wallace Jones|Wallace "Wah Wah" Jones]]' record for most points scored by a single player in the KHSAA state tournament (223).<ref name=1988quarters>{{cite news |last=Maloney |first=Mark |title=Farmer Eclipses Sweet 16 Mark in Clay Rout |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 19, 1988 |page=D7}}</ref> Farmer went on to break the record, scoring 30 points in a 91&ndash;54 win.<ref name=1988quarters />

Farmer's 18 points in the semifinals against Pleasure Ridge Park helped Clay County to a 92&ndash;90 win and a rematch in the title game against Ballard High School.<ref name=1988semis>{{cite news |last=Maloney |first=Mark |title=Rallying PRP on Losing Side of Controversy This Time |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 20, 1988 |page=C8}}</ref> Farmer set a title game record against Ballard, scoring 51 points on 20 of 32 shooting (including 9 of 14 from three-point range), but Clay County lost 88&ndash;79.<ref name=1988finals>{{cite news |last=Fields |first=Mike |title=Clay's Two-Year Domination in State Ends With 88-79 Loss |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 20, 1988 |page=C1}}</ref> Ron King set the previous title game record in 1969 with 44; only Kelly Coleman's 69-point performance in 1956 bested Farmer's 51 points in a tournament game.<ref name=1988finals /> He was selected to the all-tournament team, received a Dawahares' Sweet Sixteen Academic Scholarship Award, and was voted the tournament's MVP.<ref name=1988mvp>{{cite news |last=Maloney |first=Mark |title=Farmer MVP Again, But Wanted Title More |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 20, 1988 |page=C1}}</ref> Following the state tournament, Farmer said he was contacted by [[LSU Tigers men's basketball|LSU]], [[Vanderbilt Commodores men's basketball|Vanderbilt]], [[Virginia Cavaliers men's basketball|Virginia]], and Indiana in addition to schools who had previously recruited him.<ref name=ukmum>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=UK Isn't Talking About Recruiting of Clay's Farmer |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 22, 1988 |page=C1}}</ref>

For the season, Farmer averaged 27.1 points, 6.4 rebounds and 8.7 assists per game, all career highs.<ref name=loi>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=It's Official Now: Richie Farmer is a Kentucky Wildcat |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=April 14, 1988 |page=C1}}</ref> The only player to play in the KHSAA state tournament five times, he finished his career with records for most points scored (317) and most field goals made (127) for a career in the tournament.<ref name=1988mvp /> He posted a total of 2,793 points in his high school career.<ref name=ukonhold>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Farmer Puts UK Scholarship Offer on Hold |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 28, 1988 |page=B1}}</ref> He was named [[Kentucky Mr. Basketball]], Kentucky Associated Press Male High School Athlete of the Year, and was the leading vote-getter for the Kentucky All-State Team, appearing on 160 of 167 ballots.<ref name=appoy /><ref name=victorylane>{{cite news |last=Fields |first=Mike |title=Farmer Followed Victory Lane All the Way to Top of All-State |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=April 3, 1988 |page=C1}}</ref><ref name=mrbb>{{cite news |last=Fields |first=Mike |title=Farmer, Pehlke Both No. 1 in Kentucky Basketball |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=April 17, 1988 |page=C1}}</ref> The Clay County [[County Judge/Executive|Judge/Executive]] renamed a road outside Farmer's hometown of Machester "Richie Boulevard".<ref name=victorylane /> In a 1989 ''Lexington Herald-Leader'' poll of sportswriters and former high school coaches, Farmer was the near-unanimous choice as the best high school player in Kentucky during the 1980s.<ref name=80sbest>{{cite news |last=Fields |first=Mike |title=Farmer Tops Decade Rich with High School Basketball Stars; Clay County Boasts Player, Coach Program That Dominated 1980s |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=December 16, 1989 |page=D10}}</ref>

In May 1988, Farmer was selected to an AAU all-star team that played an exhibition game in Memorial Coliseum against an all-star team from the [[Soviet Union]].<ref name=aau1988>{{cite news |last=Fields |first=Mike |title=U.S. Tames the Soviets as Kemp Goes to War |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=May 15, 1988 |page=C1}}</ref> He scored 17 points in a 107&ndash;93 win.<ref name=aau1988 /> In the first of two matchups with Indiana's All-Star team, the Kentucky All-Stars lost 102&ndash;82; Farmer had a bad shooting performance, going 5 of 18 from the field, including 2 of 9 from three-point range, for 15 points.<ref name=1988as1>{{cite news |last=Fields |first=Mike |title=Indiana Stars Break Away Late, Win 102-82 |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=June 19, 1988 |page=C1}}</ref> In the rematch the following week, Farmer scored 19 points in a 112&ndash;100 loss.<ref name=1988as2>{{cite news |last=Fields |first=Mike |title=Kemp Leads Hoosiers to Sweep of Kentucky |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=June 26, 1988 |page=C1}}</ref>

===Recruitment===
Despite Farmer's prolific scoring, recruiters expressed concern about his small stature and lack of quickness.<ref name=chance /> Even while lauding his skills, ''Lexington Herald-Leader'' sportswriter Mike Fields wrote that Farmer had "heavy legs and slow-going style".<ref name=chance /> Regarding Farmer's size, Fields noted that, despite playing point guard, Farmer consistently [[Jump ball|jumped center]] for Clay County and could jump high enough to execute a two-handed [[slam dunk]].<ref name=chance /> The ''Herald-Leader'''s Billy Reed compared Farmer to [[Indiana Hoosiers men's basketball|Indiana]]'s [[Steve Alford]], who overcame doubts about his size, speed, and defense to become the Hoosiers' all-time leading scorer and lead them to an NCAA Championship in [[1986<U+2013>87 Indiana Hoosiers men's basketball team|1987]].<ref name=farmerred>{{cite news |last=Reed |first=Billy |title=Can You Picture Cardinal Red in Clay County? |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 23, 1988 |page=C1}}</ref>

Kentucky was believed to be Farmer's school of choice, but coaches remained non-committal about his recruitment.<ref name=ukmum /><ref name=ukonhold /> The Wildcats had seven returning guards and [[small forward]]s &ndash; Rex Chapman, [[Eric Manuel]], [[Deron Feldhaus]], [[Derrick Miller]], [[John Pelphrey]], [[Johnathon Davis (basketball)|Johnathon Davis]], and [[Sean Sutton]] &ndash; and two signed recruits at those positions &ndash; [[Sean Woods]] and [[Chris Mills]].<ref name=ukmum /> Conversely, four of their five frontcourt players &ndash; [[Winston Bennett]], [[Rob Lock]], [[Cedric Jenkins]] and [[Richard Madison]] &ndash; were graduating, and lone frontcourt signee [[Shawn Kemp]] had not yet [[Proposition 48 (NCAA)|qualified academically]].<ref name=ukmum /> On March 21, 1988, Farmer told a Lexington television station that he would no longer consider Kentucky if they did not offer him a scholarship by the weekend.<ref name=ukmum /> A week later, the ''Lexington Herald-Leader'' reported that coach [[Eddie Sutton]] extended the offer but that Farmer planned to take official visits to Western Kentucky and Vanderbilt, and would host an in-home visit with LSU coach [[Dale Brown (basketball)|Dale Brown]] before deciding whether to accept Sutton's offer.<ref name=ukonhold />

In April, Farmer played shooting guard for the North team in the Kentucky Derby Festival Classic.<ref name=kdfc>{{cite news |last=Maloney |first=Mike |title=Brewer Scores 25, South Wins Classic |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=April 2, 1988 |page=D5}}</ref> He scored 14 points on 5 of 12 shooting and grabbed 3 rebounds, but his team lost to the South team 134&ndash;125.<ref name=kdfc /> Among his teammates in the Classic was Kentucky signee Sean Woods, who told the ''Lexington Herald-Leader'' that he and Farmer had become good friends and that he hoped Farmer would choose to play for the Wildcats.<ref name=kdfc /> The paper also reported that Farmer had narrowed his list of potential college choices to three: Western Kentucky, LSU, and Kentucky.<ref name=kdfc /> Farmer took an official visit to Western Kentucky the weekend of April 9, 1988, but on April 14, the second day of the April signing period, he held a press conference at his high school gymnasium to announce that he had signed a [[National Letter of Intent]] with Kentucky.<ref name=loi /> He told the assembled crowd, "[Playing for Kentucky has] been a dream of mine as long as I can remember. Even before kindergarten, I always wanted to play for Kentucky."<ref name=loi />

==College basketball==
