===Freshman===
{{see also|1988<U+2013>89 Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball team}}
By the time Farmer arrived at Kentucky, the roster had been decimated.<ref name=trouble>{{cite news |last=Suwanski |first=Rich |title=Troubled Wildcats Happy to Begin Preseason Practice |newspaper=The Messenger-Inquirer |location=[[Owensboro, Kentucky]] |date=October 14, 1988 |page=1B}}</ref> Standout shooting guard Rex Chapman entered the [[1988 NBA Draft]], ending his collegiate eligibility.<ref name=trouble /> Sophomore Eric Manuel was held out of basketball activities pending the outcome of an investigation into his [[ACT (test)|ACT]] scores.<ref name=trouble /> Signees Shawn Kemp and Sean Woods failed to qualify academically, and Chris Mills was under investigation by the NCAA for cash allegedly sent to his father by assistant coach [[Dwane Casey]] in violation of the Association's amateurism rules.<ref name=trouble /> A viral illness forced Farmer to miss about a third of the team's preseason practices.<ref name=prime>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=UK'S Scott Priming Himself for Mean Season |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=November 1, 1988 |page=C1}}</ref> Once he was able to practice, Coach Eddie Sutton related that he lacked the conditioning to finish most practices.<ref name=adjust>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Farmer's Adjustments Typical Freshman Ones |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=October 25, 1988 |page=C1}}</ref> The ''Lexington Herald-Leader'''s [[Jerry Tipton]] later reported that Farmer had to leave practice half an hour early two days a week to attend his American History class.<ref name=handling>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Handling, Progress of Farmer a Hot Topic |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=December 15, 1988 |page=D1}}</ref> Sutton also opined that Farmer's high school competition was inferior to that of [[Los Angeles]] native Mills, but Farmer's high school coach pointed out that, during Farmer's senior season, 20 of his team's games were against teams ranked in the top 20 in their respective states.<ref name=handling /><ref name=boost>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Big-Time Games in L.A. Giving Mills Boost at UK |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=October 29, 1988 |page=D17}}</ref>

In his first collegiate game, against [[Duke Blue Devils men's basketball|Duke]], Farmer played 7 minutes and [[air ball]]ed his only shot.<ref name=firstgame>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=3 Iona Players Suspended for UK Game |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=November 23, 1988 |page=C1}}</ref> After an early season loss to Notre Dame in the Big Four Classic dropped the Wildcats' record to 2&ndash;3, Sutton noted that Farmer, Sean Sutton, and [[LaRon Ellis]] had all missed practice time with [[influenza|the flu]].<ref name=flu>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Irish Pound Lifeless Wildcats 81-65; Notre Dame's Rebounding Leads to Classic Victory |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=December 4, 1988 |page=C1}}</ref> After managing just 17 points in the Wildcats' first five games, Farmer scored 10 points in 20 minutes in the team's sixth game against [[Northwestern State Demons basketball|Northwestern State]].<ref name=nwstate>{{cite news |last=McGill |first=John |title=Shady Play Late Sealed Wildcats' Fate |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=December 8, 1988 |page=C1}}</ref> With 12 seconds to go in the game and Kentucky trailing 84&ndash;82, Farmer was whistled for an intentional foul on Northwestern State's Roman Banks while trying to draw a [[Personal foul (basketball)#Charging and blocking|charge]] on an inbounds play.<ref name=nwstate /> Banks maintained that Farmer had tugged Banks toward him and fallen down, attempting to draw the call, but Farmer and Sutton both denied the alleged chicanery.<ref name=nwstate /> Banks hit one of two free throws, and Farmer missed a potentially game-tying three-point shot at the buzzer, dropping the Wildcats to 2&ndash;4 on the season.<ref name=nwstate /> Farmer followed up with a 15-point performance in a win against [[Western Carolina Catamounts men's basketball|Western Carolina]].<ref name=wc>{{cite news |last=McGill |first=John |title=Cats May Yet Hold Some Good Surprises |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=December 11, 1988 |page=C1}}</ref> In the [[Kentucky Invitational Tournament]], where Kentucky lost its opening round game to [[Bowling Green Falcons men's basketball|Bowling Green]] before winning the third-place game against [[Marshall Thundering Herd men's basketball|Marshall]], Farmer scored 12 points in each game.<ref name=searching>{{cite news |title=Self-Searching Wildcats Greet Hoosiers |newspaper=The Messenger-Inquirer |location=[[Owensboro, Kentucky]] |date=December 20, 1988 |page=1B}}</ref>

Farmer's sudden increase in scoring prompted complaints from the fan base that Sutton disliked Farmer and was limiting his minutes out of favoritism for his son, Sean.<ref name=handling /> Some fans began to [[Booing|boo]] when Sutton, the team's starting point guard, returned to the game to replace Farmer.<ref name=boo>{{cite news |last=McGill |first=John |title=Cats' New Attitude Leads to Much-Needed Resolve |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=December 18, 1988 |page=C1}}</ref> Farmer maintained that Sutton had treated him fairly, and Sutton cited lack of practice time as the reason for Farmer's limited playing time; in early January 1989, local media reported that Farmer had been limited in practice due to right knee pain.<ref name=handling /><ref name=slow>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=UK's Mission: Slowing Down Jackson, LSU |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=January 14, 1989 |page=D3}}</ref> Questions about Farmer's playing time continued into [[Southeastern Conference]] play, even as Farmer's scoring also dropped off.<ref name=slow /><ref name=morebench>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Sutton Appeals to Bench for Relief |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=January 20, 1989 |page=D1}}</ref> By late January, Sutton publicly complained about the need for more scoring from the bench, which had produced only 29 points in the team's previous seven games.<ref name=morebench /> ''Lexington Herald-Leader'' columnist Billy Reed wrote: "Richie simply isn't ready to play at this level yet".<ref name=notready>{{cite news |last=Reed |first=Billy |title=Tough Odds No Match for Sean Sutton's Heart |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=January 22, 1989 |page=C1}}</ref>

Before a January game against [[Georgia Bulldogs men's basketball|Georgia]], two-time former [[Governor of Kentucky|governor]] [[Happy Chandler|A. B. "Happy" Chandler]] presented Farmer with the 1988 Kentucky Sportsman of the Year Award.<ref name=soy1>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Farmer Packed Two Year's Worth of Living into '88 |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=January 28, 1989 |page=D10}}</ref> The youngest person and first high school athlete ever to win the award, Farmer finished ahead of former Kentucky guard [[Pat Riley]], who had just coached the [[NBA]]'s [[Los Angeles Lakers]] to a second consecutive championship.<ref name=soy2>{{cite news |last=Engel |first=Bruce |title=Farmer is Kentucky Sportsman of Year; L.A.'s Riley Finishes 2nd in Close Vote |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=January 28, 1989 |page=D1}}</ref><ref name=pathos>{{cite news |last=Story |first=Mark |title=Farmer's Fall Not Without Its Pathos &ndash; He Held Unique Bond With Kentuckians |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=April 23, 2013 |page=C1}}</ref>

With the Wildcats' record sitting at 11&ndash;13 overall and 6&ndash;6 in conference play headed into a February road game against conference leader LSU, Farmer remained in Lexington with a combination of a stomach virus and the flu.<ref name=lsuflu>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Illness-Ridden Cats Invade LSU; Ellis, Mills Go, Farmer Stays |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=February 15, 1989 |page=C1}}</ref> Teammates LaRon Ellis, Chris Mills, and Derrick Miller had also been ill, but all recovered in time to make the trip.<ref name=lsuflu /> Farmer shot just 2 of 14 in limited minutes in the month of February.<ref name=olemiss89>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Farmer 3-Pointer Saves; UK Freshman's Only FG Beats Ole Miss 70-69 |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 2, 1989 |page=D1}}</ref> In Kentucky's final home game of the season, Farmer hit a three-pointer &ndash; his only points of the game &ndash; with two seconds left to lift the Wildcats to a 70&ndash;69 win over [[Ole Miss Rebels men's basketball|Ole Miss]].<ref name=olemiss89 /> The following game, Farmer missed a potentially game-winning {{convert|15|ft|m}} jump shot at the buzzer in a 68&ndash;67 loss at [[Mississippi State Bulldogs men's basketball|Mississippi State]] to end the Wildcats' regular season.<ref name=missst89>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=UK Fades in Stretch Again; Bomb at :02 Gives Miss. St. 68-67 Win as Wildcats Fritter Away 12-Point Lead |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 5, 1989 |page=C1}}</ref> In its first game of the Southeastern Conference Tournament the next week, Kentucky lost to Vanderbilt 77&ndash;63 in a game where Farmer missed all four of his field goal attempts.<ref name=sectourney89>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Cats Lose 77-63, Finish With 13-19 Mark |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 11, 1989 |page=D1}}</ref> Finishing with a 13&ndash;19 record &ndash; the team's worst record since the 1926-27 season &ndash; the Wildcats were not invited to any postseason tournament.<ref name=sectourney89 /><ref name=worst>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=In the Beginning, Winning Won't Be UK's Top Priority |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=November 19, 1989 |page=2}}</ref> At the team's annual postseason awards banquet, Farmer received the free throw award.<ref name=freethrow>{{cite news |title=UK Basketball Players Get Awards |agency=Associated Press |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=April 22, 1989 |page=D2}}</ref>

===Sophomore===
{{see also|1989<U+2013>90 Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball team}}
Between Farmer's freshman and sophomore years, the NCAA banned Eric Manuel from playing in any further NCAA games because of questions about the legitimacy of his ACT scores and levied a two-year postseason ban, a one-year ban on televised games, and scholarship reductions against Kentucky as punishment for payments allegedly made to the father of Chris Mills.<ref name=overcome>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Pitino Promises: 'We Will Overcome'; New UK Coach Begins Hard Job of Rebuilding |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=June 2, 1989 |page=A1}}</ref> Mills was ruled ineligible to play at Kentucky and transferred to [[Arizona Wildcats men's basketball|Arizona]]; Sean Sutton and LaRon Ellis also transferred to other schools in the wake of the sanctions.<ref name=smartmoves>{{cite news |last=Reed |first=Billy |title=Smart Moves Cap UK's Longest Winter |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=June 23, 1989 |page=D1}}</ref> Eddie Sutton resigned and was replaced by [[New York Knicks]] head coach [[Rick Pitino]].<ref name=overcome /> After recruit Henry Thomas suffered an off-season injury to his [[anterior cruciate ligament]], Kentucky was left with just 8 scholarship players, none of whom were taller than {{height|ft=6|in=8}}.<ref name=thomas>{{cite news |title=UK Recruit Thomas Likely to Miss Year |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=August 26, 1989 |page=D7}}</ref>

[[File:Rick Pitino.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Rick Pitino replaced Eddie Sutton as Kentucky's coach in 1989.]]
Pitino and newly hired strength and conditioning coach [[Ray Oliver|Rock Oliver]] instituted an intensive conditioning program.<ref name=rock>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Wildcat Conditioning; UK Players Between 'Rock' and Hard Place |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=September 22, 1989 |page=D1}}</ref> The ''Lexington Herald-Leader'' noted that Farmer lost {{convert|12|lb|kg}} in the off-season, reducing his weight to {{convert|168|lb|kg}}, and Pitino praised his improved speed and endurance.<ref name=toes2head>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=New Coaches Make Mark from Players' Toes to Heads |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=October 15, 1989 |page=C3}}</ref><ref name=charms>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Pitino Charms, Incites During Midnight Madness |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=October 16, 1989 |page=C1}}</ref> Pitino also brought [[Billy Donovan]] &ndash; who played point guard on Pitino's teams at [[Providence Friars men's basketball|Providence]] &ndash; to Kentucky as a graduate assistant to mentor the team's two point guards, Farmer and Sean Woods (now academically eligible).<ref name=donovan>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Pitino's Cats into Chapter 1 of Point Guard 101 |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=October 22, 1989 |page=C1}}</ref>

The team's first intra-squad scrimmage showcased Pitino's fast-paced, three-point-heavy style; the two teams combined to shoot 98-of-175 from the field, including 23-of-57 from three, as the Blue team defeated the White team 145&ndash;85.<ref name=bluewhite89>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Wildcats Come Out Shooting |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=October 27, 1989 |page=D1}}</ref> Farmer led the White team (the projected reserves) in scoring with 26 points, including 5-of-13 shooting from three-point range.<ref name=bluewhite89 /> In the next scrimmage, played at Farmer's alma mater, Clay County High School, Farmer scored 32 points, but the White team lost to the Blue team again, 125&ndash;117.<ref name=bluewhite289>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=A Farmer Team Suffers Rare Loss in Clay |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=November 3, 1989 |page=D5}}</ref> The teams again combined for 175 shots, and Pitino said before the game that he wanted both teams to exceed 120 points.<ref name=bluewhite289 /> Farmer sat out much of the second half of the final scrimmage due to illness but scored 17 points on 5-of-16 shooting in a 124&ndash;120 victory for the White team.<ref name=bluewhite389>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Pitino Applauds Offense Cats in Top Form in Last Scrimmage |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=November 17, 1989 |page=D1}}</ref>

After Kentucky's second game of the year &ndash; a 71&ndash;69 loss at Indiana &ndash; Pitino noted that Farmer, who had 4 points and 4 assists in the game, was benefiting from extra one-on-one coaching sessions with Donovan.<ref name=experiment>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=SEC's Experimental Six-Foul Rule a Welcome Idea for Thin UK, State |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=December 4, 1989 |page=C3}}</ref> In a December 19, 1989, victory against [[Furman Paladins men's basketball|Furman]], Farmer attempted 7 three-pointers &ndash; tied for second-most in the game &ndash; as the Wildcats set an NCAA record for most three-pointers attempted in a game with 47, besting their own record of 41 set earlier in the month against [[Tennessee Tech Golden Eagles men's basketball|Tennessee Tech]].<ref name=3record>{{cite news |last=Mathis |first=Mark C. |title=UK making habit of breaking three pointer record |newspaper=The Messenger-Inquirer |location=[[Owensboro, Kentucky]] |date=December 20, 1989 |page=1B}}</ref> A week later, Farmer set a career-high in points with 21 &ndash; including three made three-pointers &ndash; as the Wildcats set records for the most three-pointers made in a single game (21) and most points ever scored against [[North Carolina Tar Heels men's basketball|North Carolina]], but lost the game 121&ndash;110.<ref name=89careerhigh>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Good-Bad Cats Lose 121&ndash;110; Tar Heels Win Despite Record 21 'Threes' by UK |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=December 28, 1989 |page=C1}}</ref> After the game, Pitino opined that Farmer "holds back a little bit" and noted that he would expect Farmer to work hard in the off-season to reach his potential.<ref name=stone>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=UK-U of L Series 'Written in Stone,' Pitino Says |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=December 30, 1989 |page=D2}}</ref> The Wildcats closed out 1989 with a closer-than-expected 86&ndash;79 loss against eighth-ranked Louisville, but local sportswriter John McGill said Farmer had his best game to date with 10 points, 9 assists and 3 steals off the bench.<ref name=89bestgame>{{cite news |last=McGill |first=John |title=As Losses Go, it was a Triumph |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=December 31, 1989 |page=C1}}</ref>

In a January 20, 1990, contest against conference foe [[Tennessee Volunteers basketball|Tennessee]], Pitino benched senior shooting guard Derrick Miller to start the second half, giving his spot to Farmer.<ref name=wails>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Pitino 'Beats' Pelphrey, Miller Wails Away |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=January 21, 1990 |page=D1}}</ref> Farmer, who had no assists and 4 turnovers in nine minutes during the first half, responded with 7 assists and only one turnover in the second half.<ref name=wails /><ref name=juice>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Cats Turn on Juice, Beat Orange; UK Relies on Conditioning, Three-Pointers in 2nd Half to Overhaul Vols 95&ndash;83 |publisher=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=January 21, 1990 |page=D1}}</ref> Miller, who entered the game with 17:38 left, scored 17 points in the second half as the Wildcats turned a 44&ndash;39 halftime deficit into a 95&ndash;83 win.<ref name=wails /> Miller credited Pitino's decision to bring him off the bench in the second half with taking the pressure off him and helping him get more comfortable in the game.<ref name=wails /> After a mid-week loss to Auburn, Pitino announced that he would move Farmer into the starting lineup, replacing Sean Woods, for the Wildcats' January 27 contest against Ole Miss.<ref name=start>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Farmer to Replace Woods as Starter |newspaper=Lexington Herald Leader |date=January 26, 1990 |page=D1}}</ref> "We will change the lineup to try to get more concentration. We'll try Richie Farmer at the point and see what we get out of that. Right now we're not getting too much out of that position," Pitino told reporters during an SEC teleconference.<ref name=start /> In a 98&ndash;79 victory, Farmer tallied 11 points, 2 assists and no turnovers in 24 minutes; Woods registered 8 points, 4 assists, and 2 turnovers in 23 minutes off the bench.<ref name=safe>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=No Point Guard Should Feel Safe in Starting Spot Under Pitino |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=January 28, 1990 |page=D6}}</ref><ref name=buoy>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Cats Break Glass, Rebels Defense Buoys UK in 98&ndash;79 Win |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=January 28, 1990 |page=D6}}</ref> Pitino said practice performance would determine whether Woods or Farmer would start the Wildcats' next game against [[Mississippi State Bulldogs basketball|Mississippi State]], and he ultimately decided to return Woods to the starting rotation.<ref name=charge>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Kentucky Starts Charge for Top at Miss. State |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=January 31, 1990 |page=C1}}</ref><ref name=shed>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Pitino Won't Shed Woods Yet |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=December 15, 1990 |page=D1}}</ref>

On February 15, 1990, in front of a record 24,301 fans at Rupp Arena, Farmer hit six consecutive free throws to help Kentucky overcome a career-high 41 points by LSU's [[Mahmoud Abdul-Rauf|Chris Jackson]] and pull within a half-game of first place in the SEC with a 100&ndash;95 win.<ref name=1990lsu>{{cite news |last=Reed |first=Billy |title=Oh, What a Night! UK 100, LSU 95 Record Crowd Sees Wildcats Hang on for Stunning Victory |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=February 16, 1990 |page=A1}}</ref> Farmer entered the game after Sean Woods fouled out with 1:54 left, and with Kentucky leading by two with just over a minute left, LSU coach Dale Brown instructed his team to foul Farmer on each Kentucky possession to conserve the game clock and regain possession of the ball.<ref name=wrongman>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Pitino Says LSU Picked Wrong Man to Foul |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=February 17, 1990 |page=D3}}</ref> "We felt Farmer did not have much experience, and he was playing a little tight," Brown said after the game.<ref name=wrongman /> Told of Brown's instructions to foul Farmer &ndash; the team's best free throw shooter at 86% &ndash; during a post-game interview, Pitino expressed surprise.<ref name=wrongman /> "[Brown] said he purposely wanted to foul Richie Farmer? What was his reason? ...  If I had to pick a guy to shoot it in front of 50,000 people with your life at stake, it's going to be Richie Farmer shooting that free throw."<ref name=wrongman />

Less than two minutes into a subsequent game at Alabama, Farmer and walk-on Tony Cooper both left the bench when Kentucky's Reggie Hanson and Alabama's [[Robert Horry]] engaged in a fist-fight.<ref name=ejection>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Camps Won't Be How Pitino Spends Summer Vacation |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=February 25, 1990 |page=D3}}</ref> Hansen, Horry and Cooper were all ejected, but Farmer was not.<ref name=ejection /> Asked about the difference in penalties for Cooper and Farmer, official Don Ferguson admitted he did not want to hurt Kentucky's shallow rotation any further by ejecting another regular contributor.<ref name=ejection /> As a token of appreciation to the fans, after the Wildcats' February 24 "[[Senior day|Senior Day]]" win over Auburn, Pitino called his players back onto the floor and presented the individual awards usually reserved for the team's annual awards banquet.<ref name=1990seniorday>{{cite news |last=Clay |first=John |title=Wildcats Send Fans Their Best in Big Blue Love Fest at Rupp |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=February 25, 1990 |page=D4}}</ref> Farmer received the "Best Free Throw Shooter" award.<ref name=1990seniorday /> For the season, he averaged 7.0 points per game.<ref name=leave>{{cite news |title=Farmer returns after reportedly leaving UK |newspaper=The Messenger-Inquirer |location=[[Owensboro, Kentucky]] |date=September 23, 1990 |page=1B}}</ref> Fans and the media nicknamed the team "Pitino's Bombinos" for their fast-paced offense that relied heavily on the three-point shot, which contrasted sharply with the more deliberate offensive schemes run by Pitino's immediate predecessors, [[Joe B. Hall]] and Eddie Sutton.<ref name=bombinos>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Pitino Says Cats' Best Yet to Come; Depth is Seen as Difference Next Year |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 7, 1990 |page=C1}}</ref>

===Junior===
{{see also|1990<U+2013>91 Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball team}}
In September 1990, Farmer had a disagreement with strength coach Rock Oliver, returned home to Manchester, and considered leaving the Kentucky basketball team.<ref name=leave /> Pitino, who was away from campus on a recruiting visit, called Farmer and scheduled a meeting with him for the following weekend, after which Farmer decided to return to the team.<ref name=leave /> Pitino characterized the incident as "a case of someone getting down and needing a couple of hugs to get their spirits lifted a little bit".<ref name=hugs>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Pitino: Farmer's Frustrations Typical of Training Camp |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=September 25, 1990 |page=C1}}</ref> Pitino later added that he thought the transfer of point guard [[Travis Ford]] from [[Missouri Tigers men's basketball|Missouri]] &ndash; bringing additional competition in the backcourt for the 1991&ndash;92 season &ndash; may have played into Farmer's brief departure.<ref name=9192preview>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Expect to See Improved Cats Next Season |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 6, 1991 |page=C1}}</ref>

Pitino expressed uncertainty entering the season about who would replace Derrick Miller as the team's starting shooting guard.<ref name=2guard>{{cite news |last=Suwanski |first=Rich |title=Fast start important for Wildcats, Pitino says |newspaper=The Messenger-Inquirer |location=[[Owensboro, Kentucky]] |date=November 9, 1990 |page=1B}}</ref> Farmer was the leading candidate until suffering a bruised kidney during a public intra-squad scrimmage in early November and reaggravating the injury during another public scrimmage days later.<ref name=2guard /><ref name=brassow2guard>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Martinez Gets Sympathy for Air-Ball Debut |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=November 25, 1990 |page=C8}}</ref> Sophomore [[Jeff Brassow]] got the start for the Wildcats in their season opening win against [[Penn Quakers men's basketball|Penn]].<ref name=brassow2guard /> Farmer scored 12 points off the bench &ndash; one of six Wildcats with double-digit points &ndash; but left the game with 3:17 remaining after taking an inadvertent elbow in the back.<ref name=brassow2guard /> In the next game against [[Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball|Cincinnati]], Farmer briefly replaced starter Sean Woods at point guard after Woods committed eight turnovers in the first half, but Farmer fared little better, committing two turnovers and uncharacteristically missing two consecutive free throws.<ref name=2ndwin90>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Brassow, Mashburn, Woods, Farmer: 4 Cats Who Handled the Heat |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=November 29, 1990 |page=C4}}</ref> In the second half, after Woods picked up his fourth foul, Farmer entered the game and provided steady leadership to preserve a 75&ndash;71 win.<ref name=2ndwin90 /> In the Wildcats' third game of the year &ndash; a win over Notre Dame in the Big Four Classic &ndash; Farmer led the team in scoring with 19 points on 7-of-11 shooting; he added 4 assists and 2 steals against no turnovers in 23 minutes of play.<ref name=90nd>{{cite news |last=McGill |first=John |title=Sharp Play at Point has Cats on a Roll |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=December 2, 1990 |page=C1}}</ref>

Prior to Kentucky's December 15 matchup against [[Chattanooga Mocs basketball|Chattanooga]], Pitino publicly contemplated starting Farmer in place of Sean Woods at point and either [[Carlos Toomer]] or [[Jody Thompson (basketball)|Jody Thompson]] at shooting guard instead of Brassow.<ref name=90change>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Pitino Ponders Change in Cats' Lineup |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=December 13, 1990 |page=B1}}</ref> The day of the game, he announced Farmer would make the second start of his career at shooting guard alongside Woods at point.<ref name=shed /> Although he tied with Pelphrey for a team-high 17 points, Farmer returned to the bench for the following game against Indiana because Pitino felt he didn't have the size to defend the Hoosiers' bigger guards.<ref name="notenough">{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=17 Points Won't Keep Farmer a Starter |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=December 16, 1990 |page=C4}}</ref>

In a December 22, 1990, win against in-state rival Western Kentucky, Farmer posted a new career high with 22 points, despite missing his first five three-point attempts of the game.<ref name=seed>{{cite news |last=Donovan |first=John |title=Farmer Plants Seed and Wildcats Harvest Win &ndash; 11&ndash;0 Stretch Lifts Kentucky |newspaper=The Kentucky Post |location=[[Cincinnati, Ohio]] |date=December 22, 1990 |page=13K}}</ref> He would not approach such scoring numbers again until a February 3, 1991, contest against Georgia, when he scored 16 points after seeing extended minutes due to Woods being in foul trouble.<ref name=91ga>{{cite news |last=Donovan |first=John |title=UK Emerges Victorious in Cat-and-Dog Fight |newspaper=The Kentucky Post |location=[[Cincinnati, Ohio]] |date=February 4, 1991 |page=6K}}</ref> Farmer suffered a [[black eye]] during the game, which was notable for its physicality.<ref name=91ga /> ''[[Messenger-Inquirer]]'' sportswriter Jake Jennings also noted that Farmer relied on drives to the basket to score, as opposed to his usual penchant for shooting three-point shots.<ref name=91drives>{{cite news |last=Jennings |first=Jake |title=UK dons Sunday best for win over Georgia |newspaper=The Messenger-Inquirer |location=[[Owensboro, Kentucky]] |date=February 4, 1991 |page=1B}}</ref>

Before Kentucky's February 13 game against Tennessee, Woods was hospitalized with an "acute viral illness".<ref name=woodsill>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Cats Win One to Remember; Hanson Scores Career High of 28 as Vols Fall 85&ndash;74 |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=February 14, 1991 |page=D1}}</ref> Farmer started in his place, tallying 14 points and 7 rebounds in an 85&ndash;74 win.<ref name=woodsill /> Although Farmer also started the next game against Ole Miss, just 48 seconds into the game his knee made contact with an opponent's knee, sending him to the locker room and Woods into the game.<ref name=91olemiss>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Wildcats' Pressure Wears on Rebels, Refs, Murphy Says |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=February 17, 1991 |page=D4}}</ref> Farmer returned to score a team-high 21 points, but also suffered a scratched eye, in a win that gave Kentucky the best record in the SEC; Woods logged 9 points and 7 assists in almost 24 minutes of action off the bench.<ref name=91olemiss2>{{cite news |last=Reeves |first=Barry |title=Hanson Weaves Magic &ndash; UK Senior Helps Put UK Alone Atop Southeastern Conference Standings |newspaper=The Kentucky Post |location=[[Cincinnati, Ohio]] |date=February 18, 1991 |page=6K}}</ref> Woods returned to the starting lineup in Kentucky's next game at Vanderbilt, but Farmer remained a starter as well, replacing Jeff Brassow at shooting guard.<ref name=91vandy>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Vandy Shoots Down Cats |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=February 21, 1991 |page=C1}}</ref> He scored 13 of his team-high 19 in the first half, but Kentucky lost the game 98&ndash;87.<ref name=91vandy /> Pitino characterized Farmer as "exhausted" in the second half, playing heavy minutes in relief of Woods, who managed only 15 minutes before fouling out.<ref name=91exhausted>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Cats Run Afoul of Vandy; Commodores Hit 40 at Line, Kill Cats With 18&ndash;2 2nd-Half Run |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=February 21, 1991 |page=C1}}</ref> Two games later, Farmer hit four of his first five shots &ndash; including three 3-pointers &ndash; and finished with a team-high 16 in a win against Alabama.<ref name=plaid>{{cite news |last=McGill |first=John |title=This UK Game has Wimp Seeing Plaid |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=February 27, 1991 |page=C1}}</ref><ref name=91bama>{{cite news |last=Donovan |first=John |title=UK, Pitino Notch Win by Imitating Opponents |newspaper=The Kentucky Post |location=[[Cincinnati, Ohio]] |date=February 27, 1991 |page=6K}}</ref> Farmer notched 20 points &ndash; one behind team leader [[Jamal Mashburn]] &ndash; in Kentucky's final game of the season, a 114&ndash;93 win over Auburn.<ref name=91final>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Cats Parade Past Auburn 114&ndash;93; Pounding Gives UK SEC's Best Record |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 3, 1991 |page=D1}}</ref> The win pushed Kentucky to a conference-best 14&ndash;4 record, but an SEC rule forbade declaring a team the regular season champion if they were ineligible for postseason play, as Kentucky was.<ref name=91final />

Farmer was one of five players to average double-digit points per game (10.1); it was the first time since Kentucky's 1977&ndash;78 championship team that so many players had averaged double-digit scoring.<ref name=fivedd>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Powers Above, Below Enter Pitino-Davis Feud |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 10, 1991 |page=D3}}</ref> At the team's postseason awards banquet, Farmer received the Free Throw Award for the third straight year and was also named the team's Most Improved Player.<ref name=91mip>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=UK's Hanson Wins Five Awards, Has One Named in His Honor |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 3, 1991 |page=D4}}</ref> Pitino named the four rising seniors &ndash; Farmer, Pelphrey, Woods, and Feldhaus &ndash; co-captains for the upcoming season.<ref name=cocaptains>{{cite news |title=Wildcats' celebration continues with parade |newspaper=The Messenger-Inquirer |location=[[Owensboro, Kentucky]] |date=March 3, 1991 |page=6B}}</ref>

===Senior===
{{see also|1991<U+2013>92 Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball team}}
Shortly after the team's first practice in October 1991, Pitino again commented on Farmer's improved conditioning, calling it his "biggest surprise" of the early practices.<ref name=lockedin>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Four Positions Locked in for Opener, Pitino Says |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=October 18, 1991 |page=B1}}</ref> He also announced that seniors Sean Woods and John Pelphrey would join Jamal Mashburn in the starting lineup &ndash; as the team's point guard, small forward, and power forward, respectively &ndash; while senior Deron Feldhaus would reprise his "[[sixth man]]" role from the previous season.<ref name=lockedin /> Farmer was projected to compete with junior college transfer Dale Brown for the starting shooting guard spot.<ref name=pressure>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=If Pressure is Back on UK, Pitino Says Cats Not Feeling It |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=October 19, 1991 |page=D10}}</ref> At the team's annual [[Midnight Madness (basketball)|Midnight Madness]] scrimmage, Farmer joined the announced starters and sophomore [[Gimel Martinez]] on the Blue team, which defeated the White team 67&ndash;54.<ref name=91bbm>{{cite news |last=Reeves |first=Barry |title=Going Mad &ndash; UK Opens Practice With a New Twist |newspaper=The Kentucky Post |location=[[Cincinnati, Ohio]] |date=October 21, 1991 |page=8K}}</ref> Farmer had 18 points, including 4 of 6 made three-point baskets.<ref name=91bbm /> Forbidden from holding off-campus scrimmages by new NCAA regulations, Kentucky played its only public preseason scrimmage in Memorial Coliseum; Farmer joined the White team, scoring 21 points on 6-of-12 shooting in a losing effort.<ref name=91bws>{{cite news |last=Donovan |first=John |title=Talented Freshmen Raise Hopes at UK &ndash; Fans Get Look at Newcomers |newspaper=The Kentucky Post |location=[[Cincinnati, Ohio]] |date=October 30, 1991 |page=10K}}</ref>

Suffering from the flu, Farmer did not play in the Wildcats' season-opening win against [[West Virginia Mountaineers men's basketball|West Virginia]] in the [[NIT Season Tip-Off|Preseason NIT]].<ref name=91opener>{{cite news |last=Donovan |first=John |title=Inspired Ford Puts Kentucky in Driver's Seat |newspaper=The Kentucky Post |location=[[Cincinnati, Ohio]] |date=November 21, 1991 |page=8K}}</ref> He played in the following game, but missed all seven of his shots as Kentucky was eliminated from the tournament by [[Pitt Panthers men's basketball|Pitt]] 85&ndash;67, the team's worst home loss since 1988.<ref name=91pitt>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Bye-Bye, N.Y.! Pitt Stings Cats 85&ndash;67; UK Goes Cold as Pittsburgh Advances in Pre-Season NIT |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=November 23, 1991 |page=D1}}</ref><ref name=layoff>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=UK Ends Layoff, Lays it on 90&ndash;69 |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=December 5, 1991 |page=C1}}</ref> Farmer came off the bench in the Wildcats' next game &ndash; a 90&ndash;69 win over [[UMass Minutemen basketball|UMass]] &ndash; but matched his career-high with 22 points, including a perfect 10-of-10 from the free throw line; he saw extended minutes in the game due to a season-ending knee injury to Jeff Brassow.<ref name=layoff /> UMass coach [[John Calipari]] called Farmer "the difference in the game".<ref name=layoff />

During the non-conference season, Farmer made notable plays late in important games, including a game-clinching rebound against Indiana and a key three-pointer in the waning minutes of a game against Ohio.<ref name=primetime>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title='Prime-Time' Farmer Usually Finds Way to Get His Name in Headlines |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=December 28, 1991 |page=D2}}</ref> In a January 2, 1992, game against Notre Dame, Farmer entered the game after just three minutes when starter Dale Brown sprained his ankle.<ref name=ch28>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Wildcats Hit Benchmark, Rip Irish 91&ndash;70 |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=January 3, 1992 |page=B1}}</ref> In the first half, he equaled his career high of 22 points &ndash; including five three-point baskets &ndash; en route to a new career-high of 28 in a 91&ndash;70 victory.<ref name=ch28 /> This performance notwithstanding, complaints from the fan base about Farmer's lack of playing time &ndash; he averaged 17.7 minutes per game through early February &ndash; grew louder and eventually became the subject of media interest.<ref name=farmerpt>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Some UK Fans Want More &ndash; Of Richie, That Is; Farmer's Playing Time Hot Topic, but Pitino, Player Say It's Non-Issue |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=February 7, 1992 |page=B1}}</ref> In January, two of Kentucky's smaller newspapers printed articles on the subject &ndash; one speculating that Pitino was intentionally holding Farmer back so Farmer's popularity wouldn't eclipse his own.<ref name=farmerpt /><ref name=pitinorebuke>{{cite news |title=Pitino Voices Displeasure With Farmer Article |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=February 8, 1992 |page=D3}}</ref> Kentucky [[Beat reporting|beat writer]] Jerry Tipton addressed the topic at length in a ''Lexington Herald-Leader'' column on February 8, drawing a rebuke from Pitino, who called the issue a "non-story".<ref name=farmerpt /><ref name=pitinorebuke />

In late January, shortly before the Tipton article appeared, Pitino decided to start Farmer against Ole Miss.<ref name=92omstart>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=With Ole Miss on Menu, UK Feasts Again; Mashburn Scores 24, Cats Roll 96&ndash;78 |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=January 30, 1992 |page=C1}}</ref> He believed starting Woods and bringing Brown off the bench would allow him to have one of his two best defenders on the floor more often; he also believed Farmer's height would not be a liability against Ole Miss' smaller starting guards.<ref name=92omstart /> Farmer scored 10 points on 4-of-10 shooting and led the team with 6 rebounds in a 96&ndash;78 victory.<ref name=92omresult>{{cite news |last=Donovan |first=John |title=UK Climbs Back Atop SEC Eastern Division &ndash; Riddick's Woes Are Only Drama |newspaper=The Kentucky Post |location=[[Cincinnati, Ohio]] |date=January 30, 1992 |page=8K}}</ref> Pitino then decided to start Farmer and fellow reserve Deron Feldhaus in Kentucky's next game against LSU, hoping to draw Tigers center [[Shaquille O'Neal]] farther from the basket by starting better shooters.<ref name=92lsu>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=UK Plans Bombing Raid on LSU, O'Neal |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=February 2, 1992 |page=D1}}</ref> The strategy was not successful &ndash; Farmer shot 2-of-9 and Feldhaus 1-of-10 in a 74&ndash;53 loss &ndash; but Pitino announced that Farmer would continue to start because he was exhibiting more shooting confidence than Kentucky's other guards.<ref name=back2back20>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=UK Loses Back-to-Back Road Games by 20-Plus For Only 2nd Time Ever |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=February 3, 1992 |page=C4}}</ref><ref name=lsudoom>{{cite news |last=Donovan |first=John |title=Poor Shooting Dooms Free-Falling Wildcats |newspaper=The Kentucky Post |location=[[Cincinnati, Ohio]] |date=January 30, 1992 |page=8K}}</ref> Farmer responded with 16 points, including four 3-pointers, in a 85&ndash;67 victory over Auburn.<ref name=unlikelypair>{{cite news |title=Unlikely Pair Comes Through to Spark Kentucky |newspaper=The Kentucky Post |location=[[Cincinnati, Ohio]] |agency=Associated Press |date=February 10, 1992 |page=6K}}</ref> He continued to start for the Wildcats for the rest of the regular season, culminating in a Senior day win against Tennessee, when he scored 11 of Kentucky's first 16 points and saw extended minutes after fellow senior Sean Woods was ejected for fighting with the Volunteers' [[Jay Price]].<ref name=winner /><ref name=seniorday>{{cite news |last=Mathias |first=Mark |title=It Was a Special Day at Rupp Arena Saturday |newspaper=The Messenger-Inquirer |location=[[Owensboro, Kentucky]] |date=March 8, 1992 |page=1B}}</ref>

With the team's probation over, Farmer and the other three seniors played in their first &ndash; and only &ndash; postseason games in the 1991&ndash;92 season.<ref name=firstandonly>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=UK Seniors Getting Ready For 'First and Only Chance' |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 13, 1992 |page=B1}}</ref> After an opening round win against Vanderbilt in the SEC Tournament in [[Birmingham, Alabama]], Kentucky won its third meeting of the season with LSU 80&ndash;74 in the second round; the Tigers were without star center Shaquille O'Neal, who was suspended for fighting with Tennessee's [[Carlus Groves]] in his team's opening round victory.<ref name=firstandonly /><ref name=noshaq>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=With No Shaq to Attack, UK Topples LSU; Free to Score Inside, Cats Roll On, 80&ndash;74 |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 15, 1992 |page=D1}}</ref> In the finals, Kentucky faced three-time defending tournament champion Alabama, which was without forward [[Andre Perry (basketball)|Andre Perry]], who suffered a broken foot in the semifinals against Arkansas.<ref name=92sect>{{cite news |last=Culpepper |first=Chuck |title=UK Wins SEC With Flourish; Virtuosos Seize Moment to Savor Sweet Victory |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 16, 1992 |page=A1}}</ref> Star sophomore Jamal Mashburn led all scorers with 28 points on 12-of-14 shooting, en route to a 80&ndash;54 victory and tournament Most Valuable Player honors.<ref name=92secwin>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Wildcats Ride Over Low Tide to SEC Title; Mashburn Gets 28 as UK Wears Out Alabama 80&ndash;54 in Tournament Finals |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 16, 1992 |page=C1}}</ref> Mashburn, who shot 26-for-31 in the Wildcats' three tournament games, said of his performance, "At the beginning of the season, I told the four seniors 'this is the only thing I can give you. I can't give you any presents, but I can give you an SEC championship. We gave them a present they really deserved."<ref name=mashmvp>{{cite news |last=Mathias |first=Mark |title=Mashburn Keeps Promise of Victory |newspaper=The Messenger-Inquirer |location=[[Owensboro, Kentucky]] |date=March 16, 1992 |page=4B}}</ref>

Kentucky was seeded second in the East Region of the [[1992 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|1992 NCAA Tourment]].<ref name=92sect /> The Wildcats held a narrow 62&ndash;59 lead with 8:25 to play in their first round matchup against [[Colonial Athletic Association]] champion [[Old Dominion Monarchs basketball|Old Dominion]] when Farmer hit a layup that keyed a decisive four-and-a-half-minute, 15&ndash;2 run, helping Kentucky to a 88&ndash;69 victory.<ref name=92firstround>{{cite news |title=Kentucky's Return to NCAAs a Success &ndash; Wildcats Rout Old Dominion |newspaper=The Seattle Times |agency=Time News Services |date=March 20, 1992 |page=D6}}</ref> Kentucky's next game, against [[Iowa State Cyclones men's basketball|Iowa State]], was decided at the free throw line. Kentucky was called for 29 fouls in the game, and Iowa State hit 34-of-38 free throws, but in the final 1:27 of the game, Kentucky shot 14 free throws &ndash; making 11 &ndash; to win the game 106&ndash;98.<ref name=92secondround>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Wildcats Left Standing After 106&ndash;98 Duel; Woods Rules in Fast Pace as Iowa State Falls Short |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 23, 1992 |page=C1}}</ref> Farmer, who finished with 14 points, hit four consecutive free throws in the final minute of the game.<ref name=92secondround /> After the game, Pitino commented, "If not for Richie Farmer, we don't win the game."<ref name=credit4win>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Orr Blasts Officials For Not Keeping Pitino in Box |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 23, 1992 |page=C4}}</ref> In the regional semifinals, the Wildcats faced a rematch with third-seeded UMass. After the Minutemen cut a 20-point Kentucky lead to 2 with almost six minutes remaining in the game, UMass coach John Calipari was whistled for a technical foul for leaving the [[coach's box]] while arguing that one of his players had been fouled on a loose ball rebound; Farmer, who finished with 7 points, made the resulting free throws, starting an 11&ndash;2 run that helped Kentucky to an 87&ndash;77 win.<ref name=92regionalsemis>{{cite news |title=Technically, Kentucky Capitalizes on Call |newspaper=The Charlotte Observer |agency=Observer News Services |date=March 27, 1992 |page=6B}}</ref>

In the regional finals, Kentucky trailed top-seeded Duke by 12 in the second half, but battled back to force overtime.<ref name=92end>{{cite news |last=Culpepper |first=Chuck |title=UK Had Won Hearts |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 29, 1992 |page=A1}}</ref> With 2.1 seconds left in overtime, Sean Woods hit a running bank shot to put Kentucky up one.<ref name=92end /> Then, Duke's [[Christian Laettner]] caught a long inbounds pass, faked right, and hit a shot a the buzzer to give Duke the 104&ndash;103 victory.<ref name=92end /> [[The Shot (Duke<U+2013>Kentucky)|The game]], which ended Farmer's playing career, is widely regarded as one of the greatest college basketball games of all time.<ref name=sigreatest>{{cite news |last=Waxman |first=Matthew |title=16 Greatest Games |date=March 11, 2004 |newspaper=Sports Illustrated |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2004/sioncampus/03/10/greatest_games0311/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405100205/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2004/sioncampus/03/10/greatest_games0311/ |archivedate=April 5, 2012 |accessdate=July 30, 2014}}</ref><ref name=usatodaygreatest>{{cite news |last=Douchant |first=Mike |title=Greatest 63 games in NCAA Tournament history |newspaper=USA Today |date=March 25, 2002 |url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/college/basketball/men/02tourney/greatest-games.htm |accessdate=July 30, 2014}}</ref> Duke coach [[Mike Krzyzewski]] later recalled, "The thing I'll always remember about that game is Richie Farmer's face as the ball went in. That, to me, helped me to have a better understanding of that game. ... To me, that was the deepest emotion that was on the court, the emotion that was on Richie Farmer's face."<ref name=92face>{{cite news |last=Culpepper |first=Chuck |title=Emotions High for UK Grudge Match with Duke |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 22, 1998 |page=A1}}</ref> Describing the impact of the game, Jerry Tipton wrote, "On one fateful night, the Cats obliterated any lingering association with $1,000 packages and academic fraud. Alluring images of courage, honest effort and heartracing excitement became symbols of UK basketball."<ref name=erase>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Seniors, Pitino Erased Kentucky's 'Shame' With Game of Games |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 30, 1992 |page=C1}}</ref> Local media gave the seniors the nickname "The Unforgettables".<ref name=unforgettables>{{cite news |last=Story |first=Mark |title=Year After Scaling Pinnacle, Unforgettables Still Thriving |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=February 6, 1993 |page=D10}}</ref> Collectively, they were voted as the ''Lexington Herald-Leader'''s 1992 Sportsmen of the Year.<ref name=92soty>{{cite news |last=Story |first=Mark |title=Voters Couldn't Forget UK Seniors; True Blue Basketballers Edge Pitino as Best of  '92 |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=February 6, 1993 |page=D10}}</ref>

[[File:Richie-Farmer-jersey.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Farmer's jersey hangs in the rafters at [[Rupp Arena]].]]
At the team's annual awards night, Farmer won the award for fewest turnovers per minute played (32 in 705 minutes), but the free throw award &ndash; won by Farmer the previous three years &ndash; went to Gimel Martinez.<ref name=retired>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Wildcats' Send-Off Surprise: UK Shocks Seniors, Retires Jerseys |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=April 8, 1992 |page=C1}}</ref> Athletics director [[C. M. Newton]] surprised the four seniors by hanging their jerseys in the rafters at Rupp Arena.<ref name=retired /> In so doing, he violated the standards for the honor set by former athletics director [[Cliff Hagan]].<ref name=standardsvio>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Newton Broke UK's Policy for Retiring Jerseys |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=April 19, 1992 |page=D3}}</ref> Those guidelines held that honorees must have completed a degree from the university and be at least 10 years removed from the end of their athletic eligibility.<ref name=standardsvio /> Newton cited the seniors' "unusual and outstanding contributions" to the program as reasons to make an exception to the standards, adding, "I won't say there never will be another exception, but the likelihood of another is not great."<ref name=standardsvio /> Sportscaster [[Cris Collinsworth]] protested Newton's action because it honored the seniors before other program standouts like [[Kyle Macy]] and [[Rick Robey]].<ref name=standardsvio />

After the season, the four seniors participated in a 21-city barnstorming tour of the state, playing against a group of local players in each city.<ref name=40Ktour>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Tour May Net UK's Seniors $40,000 Each |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=April 26, 1992 |page=D1}}</ref> At the game in Farmer's hometown of Manchester, Farmer scored 107 points for the seniors' team before switching to the Clay County team for the remainder of the game, hitting an additional three-pointer for a total of 30.<ref name=110exhibition>{{cite news |title=Farmer's 110 Points Lead Seniors in Clay Co. |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=April 21, 1992 |page=C3}}</ref> Pelphrey hit a three to give the seniors &ndash; without Farmer &ndash; a 179&ndash;176 lead with 25 seconds left in the game, and the three seniors triple-teamed Farmer to prevent him from getting a shot off to tie the game.<ref name=110exhibition /> Twenty percent of the proceeds from each game benefited local charities, and another twenty percent of the total proceeds from the tour was divided between the University of Kentucky Library Fund, [[Big Brothers Big Sisters of America|Big Brothers Big Sisters]], and AIDS Volunteers of Lexington.<ref name=tourproceeds>{{cite news |last=Clay |first=John |title=UK Seniors Give to Library, Charities |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=May 5, 1992 |page=C1}}</ref>

==Post-playing career==
In August 1992, Antex Publishing of Lexington released Farmer's [[autobiography]] entitled ''Richie''.<ref name=richie>{{cite news |title=Glory Days &ndash; UK Star Richie Farmer Shares Ups, Downs of Career in New Book |newspaper=The Kentucky Post |location=[[Cincinnati, Ohio]] |date=August 7, 1992 |page=2K}}</ref> In addition to the standard printing, the publisher offered a special edition of the book in which direct quotes from Farmer were rendered in blue type, similar to the words of [[Jesus]] in [[red letter edition]]s of the [[Bible]].<ref name=blueletter>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=We Swear on Stack of 'Richie's, Farmer Quotes Deemed Divine |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=August 16, 1992 |page=C3}}</ref> Long-time Wildcats radio broadcaster [[Cawood Ledford]] wrote the book's [[foreword]].<ref name=foreword>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Farmer Accentuates Positive in Book About His First 23 Years |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=August 19, 1992 |page=C6}}</ref> By the end of October, the book had sold 30,000 copies, and a second printing from the publisher was ordered.<ref name=2ndprinting>{{cite news |title=Colleges &ndash; UK Loses Two More Starters to Injuries |newspaper=The Kentucky Post |location=[[Cincinnati, Ohio]] |date=October 29, 1992 |page=8K}}</ref> Farmer participated in several book signings across the state, as well as filming television advertisements for local products and conducting speaking engagements for dental insurance provider [[Delta Dental]] to promote good oral health in his native eastern Kentucky.<ref name=unforgettables />

Farmer continued taking classes at Kentucky with support from the Cawood Ledford Scholarship fund &ndash; designated to help University of Kentucky athletes who have exhausted their athletic eligibility finish their degrees &ndash; and in 1995, earned a [[bachelor of science]] degree with a double major in agricultural economics and agribusiness management.<ref name=95grad>{{cite news |last=Bailey |first=Rick |title=Murray, WKU Men's Basketball Still Trail in Graduation Rates |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=July 23, 1995 |page=C1}}</ref><ref name=clsf>{{cite news |last=Coomes |first=Mark |title=15 Years After Last Hurrah, Ex-Center Earns Degree |newspaper=The Seattle Times |date=July 28, 1996 |page=D4}}</ref> After graduation, he briefly worked in [[sport marketing|sports marketing]] in Lexington before returning to Manchester to join his father in the insurance business.<ref name=undeterred>{{cite news |last=Estep |first=Bill |title=Richie Farmer Shoots for Three Election Wins; He is Undeterred After Recent Bumps |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=July 28, 1996 |page=A9}}</ref><ref name=insurance>{{cite news |last=Hicks |first=Jack |title=White Knuckles, Open Eyes as Feldhaus Watched Game |newspaper=The Kentucky Post |location=[[Cincinnati, Ohio]] |date=March 25, 1998 |page=1K}}</ref> In addition to selling insurance, Farmer also got his securities license to sell annuities, and eventually rose to become vice-president of Kentucky Financial Group.<ref name=undeterred /><ref name=fvf>{{cite news |last=Henderson |first=Feoshia |title=It's Farmer Versus a Farmer &ndash; Two in Race for Agriculture Post |newspaper=The Kentucky Post |location=[[Cincinnati, Ohio]] |date=September 26, 2003 |page=K1}}</ref>

On April 15, 1998, Farmer married Rebecca Ann Morgan.<ref name=divorce>{{cite news |last=Spears |first=Valarie Honeycutt |title=Wife Petitions for Divorce from Farmer &ndash; Access to Household Finances at Issue |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=April 10, 2011 |page=B1}}</ref> The couple had three sons &ndash; Richard III ("Trey") and Ryan, born on November 30 in 1996 and 1998, respectively, and Tate, born in 2001.<ref name=fvf /><ref name=eclipse>{{cite news |last=Culpepper |first=Chuck |title=Farmer's Feat Eclipses Loss |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=June 24, 1999 |page=D1}}</ref>

Farmer was inducted into the KHSAA Hall of Fame in 1998 and the Kentucky Athletic Hall of Fame in 2002.<ref name=khsaahof>{{cite news |title=Sixteen to be Inducted Into Hall of Fame Tonight |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 17, 1998 |page=D2}}</ref><ref name=kahof>{{cite news |title=Farmer, Cooksey Enter Hall |newspaper=The Kentucky Post |location=[[Cincinnati, Ohio]] |date=July 29, 2002 |page=7K}}</ref> He was one of 88 inaugural members of the University of Kentucky Athletics Hall of Fame in 2005 and one of 16 inaugural members of the Kentucky High School Basketball Hall of Fame in 2012.<ref name=ukhof>{{cite news |last=Tipton |first=Jerry |title=Couch a True Diaper Dandy in New Role as Father &ndash; Quarterback Plans to Attend UK Hall of Fame Ceremonies &ndash; Unless NFL Calls |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=September 4, 2005 |page=C3}}</ref><ref name=kyhsbbhof>{{cite news |title=First Class for High School Hall of Fame &ndash; 16 Ky. Stars to be Inducted in Elizabethtown on Saturday |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=July 11, 2012 |page=B5}}</ref> "The Unforgettables" were honored on a limited edition collector's bottle of [[Maker's Mark]] [[Bourbon whiskey|bourbon]] in 2007.<ref name=mm>{{cite news |title='Unforgettables' Made Their Mark |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 31, 2007 |page=B3}}</ref>

==Political career==
===First term as Commissioner of Agriculture===
On January 28, 2003, Farmer announced he would seek the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nomination for Kentucky Agriculture Commissioner.<ref name=agannounce>{{cite news |last=Brammer |first=Jack |title=Ex-UK Star Wants to be 'Unforgettable' &ndash; Richie Farmer Files to Run for State Ag Chief |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=January 28, 2003 |page=B4}}</ref> In his announcement, he acknowledged that he had never operated a farm, but noted that he knew many farmers and held a degree in an agriculture-related field.<ref name=agannounce2>{{cite news |title=Koenig, Grayson Won't Face Primary |newspaper=The Kentucky Post |location=[[Cincinnati, Ohio]] |date=January 29, 2003 |page=A9}}</ref> Ellen Williams, chair of the state's Republican Party, said Farmer's candidacy would bring "star quality" to a down-ballot race (i.e. state offices other than governor and lieutenant governor).<ref name=agannounce /> No Republican had been elected to any of those offices since 1967.<ref name=agannounce2 />

Farmer waited until three weeks before the [[primary election]] to begin seriously campaigning and focused on population centers such as Lexington, Louisville, [[Bowling Green, Kentucky|Bowling Green]], and the [[Northern Kentucky]] area, where Republican voters were more concentrated.<ref name=03primaryresults>{{cite news |last=Patton |first=Janet |title=Ag Chief: Baesler Faces Farmer &ndash; Winners Tied to UK Hoops |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=May 21, 2003 |page=A16}}</ref> At that time, campaign finance reports showed that Farmer had spent about half of the $36,055 raised for his campaign, while his opponent, Leonard "Buck" Beasley, had raised only $450 and spent nothing.<ref name=03primaryspending>{{cite news |last=Biesk |first=Joe |title=Democrats Lead Money Races &ndash; Stumbo, Luallen Dominating Foes in Primary Fields |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=April 25, 2003 |page=B5}}</ref> While he proposed no major changes to the operation of the agriculture department, Farmer emphasized teamwork as a means to improve the state's agricultural sector, cited the need to find new markets for Kentucky agricultural products, and expressed a desire to improve the public perception of the agriculture industry, saying "Farmers have a great story to tell, and I will use any name recognition I have gained through my experience with UK basketball to help them tell it."<ref name=03primary>{{cite news |last=Schreiner |first=Bruce |title=Candidate Urges Higher Cigarette Tax &ndash; Ag Commissioner Hopefuls Talk About Platforms |newspaper=The Kentucky Post |location=[[Cincinnati, Ohio]] |date=April 16, 2003 |page=C2}}</ref><ref name=03primary2>{{cite news |last=Patton |first=Janet |title=Farming Outlook Fraught with Uncertainty &ndash; Commissioner of Agriculture |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=May 16, 2003 |page=B1}}</ref><ref name=03primaryresults2>{{cite news |last=Schreiner |first=Bruce |title=Baesler Versus Farmer in Commissioner Race |newspaper=The Kentucky Post |location=[[Cincinnati, Ohio]] |date=May 21, 2003 |page=K6}}</ref> He also raised the possibility of engaging other former basketball players to promote the work of the agriculture department and indicated that he would lobby to have half of Kentucky's allocation of the [[Tobacco Master Settlement Agreement]] directed to the state's Agriculture Development Board.<ref name=03primaryresults />

With 109,742 votes &ndash; 79 percent of the total cast &ndash; Farmer garnered more votes than any other Republican candidate for any office on the ballot ''en route'' to winning the nomination.<ref name=03primaryresults2 /><ref name=differences>{{cite news |last=Alessi |first=Ryan |author2=Brammer, Jack |title=Now to Find the Issues &ndash; Candidates Have Yet to Outline Real Differences |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=May 22, 2003 |page=A1}}</ref> The victory set up a general election contest against Democratic nominee Alice Woods Baesler, a state agriculture department aide and wife of former [[United States House of Representatives|Congressman]] and Kentucky basketball player [[Scotty Baesler]].<ref name=03primaryresults2 /> Bolstered by his significantly higher name recognition, Farmer led an early July [[SurveyUSA]] poll 61% to 33% over Baesler.<ref name=03poll>{{cite news |last=Kinney |first=Courtney |title=Poll's Early Reading: Fletcher by an Edge |newspaper=The Kentucky Post |location=[[Cincinnati, Ohio]] |date=July 5, 2003 |page=K4}}</ref> Baesler charged that Farmer was unqualified for the job of agriculture commissioner and that his high poll numbers and convincing primary victory were driven by his popularity as a basketball player, criticizing him for featuring his status as a member of "The Unforgettables" in his campaign literature.<ref name=fvf /> Farmer responded that his college degree qualified him to be agriculture commissioner and said his need to continue his day job to support his family often kept him away from the campaign trail where he could expound more on his ideas for running the Department of Agriculture.<ref name=fvf />

At an August debate in [[Owensboro, Kentucky|Owensboro]], Farmer proposed the cross-promotion of Kentucky agricultural products and the [[List of Kentucky state parks|state park system]], awarding points for buying Kentucky produced groceries that could be redeemed for souveniers and perks during stays at state parks.<ref name=03debate>{{cite news |last=Lawrence |first=Keith |title=Agriculture Commissioner Candidates Tout Ideas at Debate |newspaper=The Messenger-Inquirer |location=[[Owensboro, Kentucky]] |date=August 8, 2003 |page=4}}</ref> On October 21, ''[[The Kentucky Post]]'' gave Baesler its endorsement, contrasting her experience running a farm and her involvement with the agriculture department to Farmer's lack of agriculture experience and frequent absence at campaign events.<ref name=03kypostendorse>{{cite news |title=A True Farmer |newspaper=The Kentucky Post |location=[[Cincinnati, Ohio]] |date=October 21, 2003 |page=K4}}</ref> Later that week, the ''Lexington Herald-Leader'' also endorsed Baesler, and followed up the next day with an article noting that, as of October 3, nearly one-third of the $87,825.20 Farmer had spent during the campaign went to relatives &ndash; including his parents, brother, sister, and in-laws &ndash; for salaries and campaign-related reimbursements.<ref name=family>{{cite news |last=Patton |first=Janet |title=Farmer Relatives Draw Salaries from Campaign Coffers &ndash; Father is Paid $20,000 to Serve as Treasurer |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=October 26, 2003 |page=B1}}</ref><ref name=03lhlendorsement>{{cite news |title=A Help to Farmers &ndash; Baesler Has Credentials for Agriculture Post |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=October 24, 2003 |page=A12}}</ref> Interviewed by phone, Farmer responded, "[My family has] probably worked 60, 70, 80 hours a week campaigning for me trying to get me elected. I don't think we have done anything wrong."<ref name=family /> Richard Beliles, chairman of campaign finance watchdog Common Cause of Kentucky, said Farmer's actions were not illegal but were "rather odd".<ref name=family /> Farmer overcame the bad press, however, to take the election by a vote of 575,049 to 466,321.<ref name=farmerscores>{{cite news |last=Lockwood |first=Frank E. |title=Farmer Scores in Agriculture Race |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=November 5, 2003 |page=A12}}</ref>

In April 2004, Farmer announced the formation of a committee to study the effectiveness of state owned and operated [[farmer's markets]].<ref name=fmannounce>{{cite news |title=Drug Policy Considered |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=April 3, 2004 |page=C1}}</ref> In June 2005, he was elected secretary of the [[Southern Association of State Departments of Agriculture]]; in 2007, he was elected president of the organization.<ref name=secsasda>{{cite news |title=Personnel File |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=June 27, 2005 |page=C2}}</ref><ref name=famousname>{{cite news |last=Alford |first=Roger |title=Ag Incumbent Counting on Famous Name Again |newspaper=The Gleaner |location=[[Henderson, Kentucky]] |date=May 18, 2007}}</ref> Farmer also sought to prevent an outbreak of [[vesicular stomatitis virus]] in the state's horses and cattle by banning the import of animals from 20 western counties where the virus was known to have infected animals.<ref name=vsv>{{cite news |title=State Expands Ban on Animals &ndash; Goal is to Prevent Livestock Disease |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=July 28, 2005 |page=B2}}</ref> On Farmer's advice, Governor [[Ernie Fletcher]] requested that the [[United States Department of Agriculture]] designate Kentucky as an agricultural disaster area after [[April 2007 nor'easter|an April 2007 cold snap]] devastated the state's fruit and wheat crops; the designation made Kentucky farmers eligible for low-interest federal loans to help compensate for their lost crop revenue.<ref name=april07cold>{{cite news |last=Fortune |first=Beverly |title=Freeze Takes Bite Out of Fruit Crop &ndsah; Damage Estimates Reach 95% |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=October 26, 2003 |page=B1}}</ref><ref name=april07wheat>{{cite news |title=Wheat Loss May Reach $63 Million in Kentucky |newspaper=The Gleaner |location=[[Henderson, Kentucky]] |date=April 27, 2007}}</ref><ref name=farmervwilliams>{{cite news |title=Farmer and Williams are Vying for Agriculture Post |newspaper=The Kentucky Post |location=[[Cincinnati, Ohio]] |date=October 16, 2007 |page=A5}}</ref>

In December 2004, Kentucky's Registry of Election Finance, the agency that enforces the state's campaign finance laws, hired Farmer's sister, Rhonda F. Gray, who had previously served as chair of her brother's campaign for agriculture commissioner.<ref name=sisterhired>{{cite news |title=Richie Farmer's Sister Hired for State Post &ndash; Occupational Therapist to Fill New Job at Registry of Election Finance |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=December 23, 2004 |page=D3}}</ref> Registry chair John Rogers maintained that Gray was hired on her own merits, and Gray promised to recuse herself from any work that might involve her brother's future campaigns.<ref name=sisterhired /> The following May, ''The Kentucky Post'' published excerpts from an email from Dick Murgatroyd, Fletcher's deputy chief of staff, to Transportation Cabinet officials asking them to find a job for Farmer's brother-in-law, Jamie Gray; the email indicated that Murgatroyd was responsible for finding jobs for both James and Rhonda Gray.<ref name=bilrequest>{{cite news |last=York |first=Amanda |title=Murgatroyd Facing Probe |newspaper=The Kentucky Post |location=[[Cincinnati, Ohio]] |date=May 17, 2005 |page=K1}}</ref> Gray was later hired as an administrative specialist in the Transportation Cabinet.<ref name=bilhired>{{cite news |last=Cheves |first=John |title=Fletcher Aides Leave Plentiful Trail of E-mail &ndash; Prosecutors in Hiring Inquiry Grateful for Tendancy to Message by the Hour |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=June 5, 2005 |page=A1}}</ref> Farmer denied any involvement in the hiring decisions beyond submitting recommendations for both candidates.<ref name=bilhired /> In July, Murgatroyd was [[indictment|indicted]] on 19 counts of violating the state's [[merit system]] by making politically motivated hires, including that of Jamie Gray.<ref name=murgindicted>{{cite news |last=York |first=Amanda |title=Murgatroyd Indicted &ndash; Violations Alleged in Merit Hiring |newspaper=The Kentucky Post |location=[[Cincinnati, Ohio]] |date=July 7, 2005 |page=K1}}</ref> A transportation official testified in September that Farmer had declined one job for Gray because the salary was too low and had negotiated a higher salary on the job Gray eventually got.<ref name=jobdeny>{{cite news |title=Farmer Denies Job Allegations |newspaper=The Kentucky Post |location=[[Cincinnati, Ohio]] |date=September 16, 2005 |page=K5}}</ref> Farmer called the claims "ludicrous" and "simply not true".<ref name=jobdeny />

===Second term as Commissioner of Agriculture===
Following the resignation of [[Lieutenant Governor of Kentucky|Lieutenant Governor]] [[Steve Pence]] in June 2006, Farmer was mentioned as a possible running mate for Fletcher in his [[Kentucky gubernatorial election, 2007|upcoming re-election campaign]], but Fletcher chose [[Robbie Rudolph]] instead, and Farmer announced his intent to seek re-election as agriculture commissioner.<ref name=runningmate>{{cite news |title=Farmer Says He's Focused on His Job |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=June 2, 2006 |page=A6}}</ref><ref name=reelect>{{cite news |last=Alessi |first=Ryan |title=State Candidates Keep Eye on Top Race |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=December 10, 2006 |page=B2}}</ref> In the Republican primary, Farmer faced Don Stosberg, a former budget analyst for Kentucky's [[Legislative Research Commission]].<ref name=famousname /> Again, Farmer was criticized for failing to appear at several campaign events; Stosberg told the ''Lexington Herald-Leader'', "[Farmer is] famous for three things: shooting three-point shots, not returning phone calls and not showing up."<ref name=07criticism>{{cite news |last=Massey |first=Delano R. |title=Farmer Faces Another Round of Fault Finding From GOP Foe &ndash; Democrats Staying Out of Fray |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=December 10, 2006 |page=B2}}</ref> Farmer responded that he was carrying out the duties of his office during his absences from the events.<ref name=07criticism /> Farmer countered his absences by outspending his opponent 35-to-1, investing a reported $102,000 in his campaign.<ref name=bounce>{{cite news |last=Sloan |first=Scott |title=Farmer Gets His 'Bounce' from UK Basketball &ndash; Incumbent Republican Will Face Democrate Who Spent Just $150 in Campaign |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=May 23, 2007 |page=A12}}</ref> Farmer captured 85% of the vote, defeating Stosberg by a vote of 155,576 to 26,897.<ref name=bounce /> Name recognition played a role in both parties' primaries: Farmer enjoyed high name recognition from his days as a basketball player, while the Democratic nominee, David Lynn Williams, had a name similar to that of [[President of the Kentucky Senate|Kentucky Senate President]] [[David L. Williams (politician)|David L. Williams]].<ref name=bounce />

Shortly after the primary election, Williams made a series of politically unsavvy remarks in an interview published by a weekly online magazine devoted to Kentucky agricultural issues; among the gaffes were calling the state agricultural development board and long-time Kentucky Democratic Senator [[Wendell H. Ford]] "a bunch of damn liars".<ref name=demslove>{{cite news |last=Patton |first=Janet |title=A Republican Even Democrats Love |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=October 31, 2007 |page=A1}}</ref> State Democratic chairman [[Jonathan Miller (Kentucky politician)|Jonathan Miller]] called Williams' statements "offensive" and said that several of the party's executive committee members desired to have Williams removed as the party's candidate.<ref name=demslove /> In June, Williams was arrested on [[misdemeanor]] charges of [[menacing]], [[disorderly conduct]], and [[harassment]] for allegedly threatening his niece, the city clerk of [[Glasgow, Kentucky]], because she did not produce records he had requested under Kentucky's [[Freedom of information in the United States|open records law]].<ref name=farmervwilliams /><ref name=menacing>{{cite news |title=Democrats' Candidate for Ag Chief is Charged With Menacity City Clerk |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=June 13, 2007 |page=B3}}</ref> His trial was not scheduled until after the election.<ref name=farmervwilliams />

By October, a [[Research 2000]] poll showed Farmer leading the race 54%&ndash;35%, with 11% undecided, and campaign finance documents showed that Farmer had spent $57,075 of the $168,650 he raised for his general election campaign, while Williams had raised and spent less than $1,000.<ref name=demslove /> The ''Lexington Herald-Leader'' made no endorsement in the race, stating that Farmer's lack of knowledge was obvious during his first term, but that he "looks like a farm-policy genius" compared to Williams.<ref name=lhl07endorse>{{cite news |title=Election Relic: Top Ag Job Should Become Cabinet Post |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=November 3, 2007 |page=A12}}</ref> On election day, Farmer set a record for the most votes received in an election for a constitutional office in Kentucky, garnering 641,789 (64%) to Williams' 363,188 (36%).<ref name=07reelect>{{cite news |last=Patton |first=Janet |title=Farmer Retains Post &ndash; Says He'll Stay With GOP; Top Vote-Getter in State |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=November 7, 2007 |page=A10}}</ref> During his victory speech, Farmer denied rumors that he was considering switching his affiliation to the Democratic Party.<ref name=07reelect />

Farmer asked [[United States Secretary of Agriculture|U.S. Agriculture Secretary]] [[Tom Vilsack]] for declarations of agricultural disasters in the wake of an [[January 2009 Central Plains and Midwest ice storm|ice storm in January 2009]] that endangered the state's livestock and [[2010 Tennessee floods|flooding]] that affected [[Kentucky Lake]] in 2010, damaging large portions of the state's corn, soybean, and wheat crops.<ref name=09icestorm>{{cite news |last=Patton |first=Janet |title=State Asks Federal Farm Disaster Status &ndash; Lack of Power Disrupts Water, Feed Supplies Milk Dumped |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=February 3, 2009 |page=A6}}</ref><ref name=10flooding>{{cite news |last=Capiello |first=Jante |title=Kentucky Lake to Hit Highest Level Ever &ndash; FEMA Teams Arrive to Assess Damage |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=May 17, 2010 |page=A6}}</ref> In December 2010, he launched a joint investigation with Democratic [[Attorney General of Kentucky|Attorney General]] [[Jack Conway (politician)|Jack Conway]] into claims that the Eastern Livestock company had not paid Kentucky cattlemen for $130 million in livestock.<ref name=elinvestigate>{{cite news |title=Briefs |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=December 3, 2010 |page=B8}}</ref>

===Bid for lieutenant governor===
Farmer was [[Term limits in the United States|limited to two terms]] by the [[Kentucky Constitution]], and in October 2009, the ''Lexington Herald-Leader'' reported that he was "in discussions" about running for governor in the [[Kentucky gubernatorial election, 2011|2011 election]].<ref name=11consider>{{cite news |last=Alford |first=Roger |title=Farmer Mulls Run for Governor &ndash; Former UK Star 'Looking at Options' for Republican Ticket in 2011 |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=October 28, 2009 |page=A3}}</ref> In August 2010, Farmer announced that he would be "running for something" in the upcoming election and would announce his plans within weeks after the [[Kentucky State Fair]].<ref name=something>{{cite news |last=Brammer |first=Jack |title=Farmer: Decision on Gubernatorial Bid to be After Fair &ndash; Talks with Williams About Slate |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=August 26, 2010 |page=A1}}</ref> The ''Lexington Herald-Leader'' speculated that Farmer could run for governor, [[Secretary of State of Kentucky|secretary of state]], or lieutenant governor on a ticket with Senate President David Williams.<ref name=something /> On September 1, 2010, Williams and Farmer announced that they would run as a ticket for governor and lieutenant governor, respectively.<ref name=ticketannounce>{{cite news |last=Brammer |first=Jack |title=Williams, Farmer Form Team for Governor's Race &ndash; State Senate President, Basketball Icon Going After GOP Nomination in 2011 |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=September 2, 2010 |page=A1}}</ref>

Shortly after the announcement, Farmer began to face criticism for his use of state funds during [[Great Recession|difficult economic times]] that resulted in [[austerity]] measures in most state government agencies.<ref name=stcroix>{{cite news |last=Cheves |first=John |title=Farmer's Trip Costs Taxpayers $10,000 &ndash; Other Convention Attendees Cite Lean Times, Cut Expenses |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=October 17, 2010 |page=A1}}</ref> One such criticism involved the attendance of Farmer and  three aides at the Southern Association of State Departments of Agriculture's 2010 annual meeting in [[Saint Croix, U.S. Virgin Islands|St. Croix]] at a cost of $10,000.<ref name=stcroix /> Another involved the approval of merit raises for eleven agriculture department employees in 2010 when workers in all other state government agencies received no [[cost of living]] salary increases and were required to take six unpaid [[furlough]] days.<ref name=meritraises>{{cite news |last=Musgrave |first=Beth |author2= Brammer, Jack |title=Farmer Raises Pay for 11 Workers &ndash; Ag Employees Only Ones in State to Get Merit Boosts During Belt-Tightening |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=December 3, 2010 |page=A1}}</ref> A department spokesman said the employees had taken on responsibilities for multiple jobs left unfilled by attrition.<ref name=meritraises /> "The thought process was that this was more cost-effective than hiring new people," the spokesman said.<ref name=meritraises /> Every constitutional officer in the state also donated a day's salary to the state treasury or to a charity on each of the mandatory furlough days, but Farmer refused, saying he opposed the entire concept of furlough days for government workers.<ref name=nofurlough>{{cite news |last=Cheves |first=John |title=Richie Farmer Opts Out of furlough &ndash; Six Elected Officials Volunteer Day's Pay |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=April 9, 2011 |page=A1}}</ref> After significant public criticism, Farmer apologized and decided to donate six days' worth of his salary to charity.<ref name=furloughreverse>{{cite news |last=Cheves |first=John |title=Farmer Decides to Embrace Sacrifice &ndash; Furlough Reversal Follows Criticism |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=April 27, 2011 |page=A1}}</ref>

Farmer was also criticized for his management of the agriculture department's vehicle fleet. Late in his first term, Farmer had removed the vehicles used by the Agriculture Department from the state fleet, opting to have department officials manage them separately.<ref name=agfleet>{{cite news |last=Cheves |first=John |title=Farmer Spending More on State Cars &ndash; Ag Fleet Increases as Rest of State Government Cuts Back |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=August 26, 2010 |page=A1}}</ref> In 2010, the [[Bluegrass Institute for Public Policy Solutions]], a [[free market]] [[think tank]], criticized the department's management of the vehicles under its control, citing the frequency with which the department's vehicles were being replaced.<ref name=agfleet /> The ''Lexington Herald-Leader'' noted in 2010 that the department's fleet had grown from 178 to 206 vehicles since 2007 while the state's fleet had shrunk by 5%, and that all but three of the department's vehicles were fewer than four years old.<ref name=agfleet /> A department spokesman defended the moves, citing decreased maintenance costs and higher resale values of vehicles being replaced.<ref name=agfleet /> The ''Lexington Herald-Leader'' noted that such incidents could undermine Williams and Farmer's traditional Republican message of the need for less government spending.<ref name=stcroix />

Farmer's wife Rebecca filed for divorce on April 5, 2011, claiming in court documents that she had no access to the family's finances except the salary she earned as a teacher's aide.<ref name=divorce /> On April 12, Farmer petitioned the court to dismiss his wife's divorce petition, contesting the idea that their marriage was irretrievably broken.<ref name=nodivorce>{{cite news |last=Brammer |first=Jack |title=Richie Farmer Files Response in Divorce Case &ndash; Says Marriage can be Saved |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=April 13, 2011 |page=A3}}</ref> The divorce proceedings were put on hold by mutual consent on May 26, 2011, but in a July 12 hearing, Farmer's wife asked that the judge schedule a trial date; the judge ordered mediation within 30 days instead.<ref name=divorceonhold>{{cite news |last=Brammer |first=Jack |title=Farmers' Divorce Case Put 'On Hold' &ndash; No Reason Given for Canceling Hearing |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=May 27, 2011 |page=A5}}</ref><ref name=divorceonhold>{{cite news |last=Brammer |first=Jack |title=Mediation Ordered in Farmers' Divorce Case &ndash; Candidate's Wife Wanted Trial Date Set |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=July 13, 2011 |page=A3}}</ref> The mediation failed, and a trial date was set for November 22, shortly after the gubernatorial election.<ref name=2ndmediation>{{cite news |last=Musgrave |first=Beth |title=Farmers' Divorce Trial Postponed Pending Mediation &ndash; Second Attempt at Settlement |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=November 22, 2011 |page=A3}}</ref> A second round of mediation shortly before the scheduled hearing resulted in a settlement between the parties; terms of the settlement were kept private.<ref name=divorcesettle>{{cite news |last=Brammer |first=Jack |title=Farmers Reach Settlement Days Before Divorce Trial &ndash; Couple Want Terms Kept Private |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=December 28, 2011 |page=A3}}</ref>

In the Republican gubernatorial primary, the Williams-Farmer ticket defeated businessman [[Phil Moffett]] and former [[Jefferson County, Kentucky|Jefferson County]] Judge/Executive [[Bobbie Holsclaw]].<ref name=11primary>{{cite news |last=Brammer |first=Jack |author2=Kocher, Greg |title=Williams is Ready to Rumble &ndash; But GOP Ticket Fails to Reach 50% as It Takes Aim at Beshear |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=May 18, 2011 |page=A1}}</ref> Williams and Farmer had led in opinion polling throughout the entire campaign, and neither opposing slate was able to raise enough money to engage in statewide television advertising; despite this, Williams and Farmer received only 68,502 votes, 48.2% of those cast.<ref name=11primary /> Holsclaw won the voting in her home county of Jefferson, which contains the city of Louisville and is the state's most populous.<ref name=11primary /> Moffett, a [[Tea Party movement|Tea Party]] favorite, carried the second most populous county, [[Fayette County, Kentucky|Fayette]] (which contains Lexington), as well as heavily-populated [[Daviess County, Kentucky|Daviess]], [[McCracken County, Kentucky|McCracken]], and [[Warren County, Kentucky|Warren]] counties, and several counties in Northern and [[Central Kentucky|Central]] Kentucky.<ref name=11primary />

Questions about Farmer's use of taxpayer funds continued to dog him throughout the general election campaign. Democrats demanded that Farmer reimburse the state for hotel expenses charged to the state while Farmer was conducting outreach activities at the KHSAA state basketball tournament and the Kentucky State Fair, both located fewer than {{convert|60|mi|km}} from his home.<ref name=hotels>{{cite news |last=Cheves |first=John |author2=Brammer, Jack |title=Farmer's State-Fair Tab Over $7,000 &ndash; Most Spent on Louisville Hotels |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=April 28, 2011 |page=A3}}</ref> In May, the office of Democratic State Auditor [[Crit Luallen]] notified the [[Internal Revenue Service]] that Farmer had failed to report personal use of his state vehicle as income.<ref name=suv>{{cite news |last=Cheves |first=John |title=Farmer Didn't Pay Taxes on State SUV &ndash; Personal-Use Miles Not Paid for 6 Years |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=May 4, 2011 |page=A1}}</ref> A spokesman for Farmer's office said that the personal mileage had been tracked, but a department employee had failed to forward it to the state Personnel Cabinet for reporting; he added that Farmer would file amended tax documents and have deductions taken from his wages to settle the tax liability.<ref name=suv /> The state Democratic Party filed an ethics complaint against Farmer in September based on an anonymous email sent to the Personnel Cabinet claiming that, after work hours, Farmer directed an agriculture department employee to purchase a small refrigerator with state funds and deliver it to Farmer's house.<ref name=fridge>{{cite news |last=Brammer |first=Jack |title=In Governor's Race, the Ethics Complaints Keep Coming &ndash; Commission Dismisses Accusation Against David Williams Over Gambling Winnings |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=September 7, 2011 |page=A3}}</ref> A department spokesman said Farmer spent a substantial amount of time working from a home office in 2010 due to a back injury and that the refrigerator had been moved to department offices in 2011.<ref name=fridge />

Beshear and Abramson easily defeated Farmer and Williams, carrying 90 of [[List of counties in Kentucky|Kentucky's 120 counties]].<ref name=beshearwin>{{cite news |last=Brammer |first=Jack |title=Beshear Sees Win as Vote Against 'Rank Partisanship' &ndash; Promises 'Lean and Efficient' Government in Second Term |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=November 9, 2011 |page=A1}}</ref> Days later, the ''Lexington Herald-Leader'' reported that Farmer had placed his girlfriend in a non-merit agriculture department job on October 31, 2011.<ref name=gfjob>{{cite news |title=Farmer Put Girlfriend on His Payroll &ndash; She Started Oct. 31, Gets $5,000 a Month |agency=Associated Press |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=November 19, 2011 |page=A3}}</ref> Williams confirmed that the woman was Farmer's girlfriend, but denied knowledge that she had been put on the state payroll.<ref name=gfjob /> Farmer defended the hiring, saying his girlfriend was qualified for the job, which involved administrative and clerical tasks, and that his legal team had assured him that he had followed all appropriate hiring regulations.<ref name=gfdefend>{{cite news |title=Farmer Defends Hiring of Girlfriend, Says She's Qualified &ndash; Outgoing Ag Chief Says His Legal Staff Gave OK |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=December 2, 2011 |page=A3}}</ref> Farmer's successor, Republican [[James Comer (politician)|James Comer]], fired Farmer's girlfriend a day after being sworn into office.<ref name=gffired>{{cite news |title=Briefs |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=January 5, 2012 |page=A3}}</ref>

==Post-political life==
===Investigations===
Five days after Farmer left office, Comer announced that he had requested a full audit of the department by newly elected Democratic State Auditor [[Adam Edelen]].<ref name=audit>{{cite news |last=Patton |first=Janet |title=New Ag Chief Seeks Audit &ndash; Departmental Issues Raised About Richie Farmer's Tenure |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=January 12, 2012 |page=A1}}</ref> Among the items Comer asked Edelen to investigate were 171 items of missing agriculture department property valued at about $334,000 and another 103 items worth about $146,000 that were supposed to be returned to the state as surplus but could not be accounted for.<ref name=items>{{cite news |last=Patton |first=Janet |title=$500,000 in Ag Items Unaccounted For &ndash; State Property That's Missing Includes At Least 110 Computers, 3 Vans |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=January 13, 2012 |page=A1}}</ref> A week later, Farmer returned some of the missing items.<ref name=returnitems>{{cite news |last=Patton |first=Janet |title=Farmer Gives Back Some State Equipment &ndash; 2 Laptops and 2 GPS Units Remain Missing |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=January 20, 2012 |page=A3}}</ref>

Comer and Edelen released the report on their joint probe on April 30, 2012.<ref name=12report>{{cite news |last=Patton |first=Janet |title=Ag Department Under Farmer: A 'Toxic Culture of Entitlement' &ndash; Audit Highlights &ndash; Auditor Alleges Many Abuses and Failure to Report Gifts |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=May 1, 2012 |page=A1}}</ref> It detailed a "toxic culture of entitlement" in the agriculture department under Farmer, charging that he had required state employees to conduct personal errands while on the clock, failed to report gifts in excess of $200 as required by state ethics laws, and signed timesheets authorizing payment to friends in the department &ndash; including his girlfriend &ndash; who had performed very little if any work.<ref name=12report /> Edelen confirmed that his investigation indicated that laws had been broken, and the report was turned over to the state attorney general for investigation.<ref name=12report /> Minutes after the report was released, Farmer's lawyer made a public statement in which he opined, "I don't see anything in this audit report that any law-enforcement agency is going to be excited about."<ref name=12response>{{cite news |last=Brammer |first=Jack |author2=Patton, Janet |title=Farmer's Attorney: Audit 'Political and Self-Serving' &ndash; Possibility of Criminal Inquiry Dismissed |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=May 1, 2012 |page=A1}}</ref> He conceded that Farmer had declined to be interviewed during the investigation but felt it was unfair that Farmer was not given a chance to review or comment on the final report prior to its release.<ref name=12response />

A week after the audit results were released, Kentucky's Executive Branch Ethics Commission reported that Farmer was the only constitutional officer who had failed to file a required disclosure of his 2011 finances by the required April 16 deadline.<ref name=12failuretofile>{{cite news |last=Brammer |first=Jack |title=Farmer Fails to File '11 Financial Disclosure &ndash; Former Ag Chief Only State Official Who Didn't Comply |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=May 1, 2012 |page=A1}}</ref> Farmer's attorney said the omission was "simply a matter of oversight on Richie's part given with [sic] what all has been going on."<ref name=12failuretofile /> Days later, First National Bank of Manchester filed a foreclosure suit against Farmer, alleging that no payments had been made on his $300,000 home mortgage since January 2012.<ref name=12mortgage>{{cite news |last=Brammer |first=Jack |title=Bank Sues Farmer Over Home Loan &ndash; Suit Says Ex-Official, Estranged Wife Owe $300,000 on Mortgage |agency=Associated Press |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=May 5, 2012 |page=B9}}</ref> Under terms of his pending divorce, Farmer was solely responsible for the mortgage on the house.<ref name=12mortgage /> The divorce was finalized in July, and on September 24, 2012, the house was sold at auction after Farmer was not successful in selling it himself.<ref name=foreclosed>{{cite news |last=Musgrave |first=Beth |title=Bank Buys Farmer's Former Home &ndash; Lender Will Sell it to Pay Off Loan |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=September 25, 2012 |page=A3}}</ref> Earlier that week, a judge denied Farmer's request to reduce his [[child support]] payments, which were based on his salary as agriculture commissioner.<ref name=underemployed>{{cite news |last=Musgrave |first=Beth |title=Farmer's Bid to Get Lower Support Payments is Denied &ndash; He's 'Voluntarily Underemployed' |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=September 22, 2012 |page=A5}}</ref> Farmer, who had not been employed since leaving office in January 2012, told the court that the investigation into his tenure as agriculture commissioner had made it difficult to find employment.<ref name=foreclosed /> The judge found that Farmer was "voluntarily underemployed", although he suspended the child support payments for the months of September and October 2012 in light of Farmer's recovery from an August 30 [[hip replacement]] surgery.<ref name=underemployed /> On November 9, 2012, the ''Lexington Herald-Leader'' reported that Farmer had found employment at a car dealership in Manchester.<ref name=carsalesman>{{cite news |last=Alford |first=Roger |title=Richie Farmer Joins Sales Staff at Manchester Car Dealerships &ndash; It's His First Job Since Leaving State Ag Post |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=November 9, 2012 |page=A7}}</ref>

===Charges filed===
On March 18, 2013, the Kentucky Executive Branch Ethics Commission charged Farmer with 42 state ethics violations, the most ever registered against a single individual; the previous high was 16.<ref name=42ethics>{{cite news |last=Brammer |first=Jack |title=42 Counts Allege 'Misuse of Office' &ndash; Most Ever for One Person; Sister, 6 Others Also Accused |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 19, 2013 |page=A1}}</ref> Most of the charges against him stemmed from the previous year's auditor's report, but previously unreported charges included conspiring with his sister Rhonda, who was also charged, to falsify records submitted to Rhonda's employer, the Registry of Election Finance.<ref name=42ethics /> Farmer's girlfriend was also charged for falsifying timesheets.<ref name=42ethics /> These charges were followed by five indictments by a federal [[grand jury]] on April 19, 2013, alleging four counts of converting state funds and property to personal use and one count of soliciting a bribe in exchange for a state grant.<ref name=5gjindict>{{cite news |last=Musgrave |first=Beth |author2=Brammer, Jack |title=Farmer Indicted &ndash; Former Ag Chief Accused of Misappropriating Money, Goods &ndash; Grand Jury Includes Soliciting a Bribe Among Five Counts |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=April 23, 2013 |page=A1}}</ref> U.S. Attorney Kerry B. Harvey said a federal investigation revealed that Farmer had created jobs in the department for his friends and girlfriend, who conducted personal errands for Farmer &ndash; including "building a basketball court for Farmer, placing flooring in Farmer's attic and organizing Farmer's personal effects" &ndash; while on the clock.<ref name=5gjindict /> He also said that Farmer had kept some of the gifts ordered in conjunction with the 2008 Southern Association of State Departments of Agriculture conference for his own use and allowed his family to stay in hotel rooms reserved for agriculture department employees at the Kentucky State Fair.<ref name=5gjindict /> The indictment did not specify what bribe was sought in exchange for a grant to conduct an [[all-terrain vehicle]] safety class, but the charges from the state Ethics Commission mentioned that Farmer had received three all-terrain vehicles in exchange for awarding unspecified state grants.<ref name=5gjindict /> A ''Lexington Herald-Leader'' report noted that the indictment only included events from 2008 forward because the [[statute of limitation]]s had expired for any actions prior to 2008.<ref name=guiltyplea>{{cite news |last=Brammer |first=Jack |title=Farmer to Plead Guilty &ndash; Former Kentucky Basketball Star Could Face Two Years in Prison for Abuses During His Years as Head of the State Agriculture Department |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=September 6, 2012 |page=A1}}</ref>

Farmer [[plea|pled]] not guilty to all five federal charges on April 25, 2013.<ref name=ngplea>{{cite news |last=Musgrave |first=Beth |title=Richie Farmer Pleads Not Guilty &ndash; Judge Denies Request to go to Mexico with Girlfriend Before Trial |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=April 26, 2013 |page=A1}}</ref> He was released on his own [[recognizance]], and his trial date was set for July 2.<ref name=ngplea /> [[United States magistrate judge|U.S. Magistrate]] Robert Wier denied Farmer's request to leave the country in May to celebrate his girlfriend's 40th birthday in [[Canc<U+00FA>n]], [[Mexico]].<ref name=ngplea /> Wier also ordered the recently unemployed Farmer to seek employment, surrender his [[passport]], and remain within the state until the trial.<ref name=ngplea /> In response to Farmer's lawyer's request to delay the trial until February 2014 &ndash; a request the prosecution called "excessive" &ndash; Judge [[Gregory Frederick Van Tatenhove|Gregory Van Tatenhove]] rescheduled the trial for October 22.<ref name=trialdelay>{{cite news |last=Musgrave |first=Beth |title=Federal Judge Reschedules Richie Farmer Trial for October |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=May 16, 2013 |page=A4}}</ref>

===Plea bargain and sentencing===
On September 5, 2013, Farmer's attorney filed a motion to allow Farmer to change his plea to guilty and announced that Farmer had reached a [[plea bargain]] to settle all federal and state charges against him.<ref name=guiltyplea /> Farmer would have faced maximum penalties of $250,000 and 10 years in prison for each federal charge against him.<ref name=guiltyplea /> Instead, in exchange for his guilty plea, prosecutors agreed to pursue a sentence of 21 to 27 months in federal prison and $120,500 in [[restitution]] of the $450,000 Farmer was accused of misappropriating.<ref name=pleaterms>{{cite news |last=Alford |first=Roger |title='I Let Down the People of Kentucky' &ndash; Richie Farmer, Ex-State Ag Chief and UK Basketball 'Unforgettable,' Pleads Guilty to Corruption Charges |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=September 14, 2013 |page=A1}}</ref> Additionally, Farmer pled guilty to one state charge of violating campaign finance laws in exchange for a sentence of no more than one year, served concurrently with his federal sentence.<ref name=pleaterms /> Finally, Farmer acknowledged to the Executive Branch Ethics Commission 35 of the 42 violations he had been charged with, resulting in $65,000 in fines, the most ever levied by the commission.<ref name=pleaterms /> Farmer's attorney indicated that U.S. Attorney Kerry Harvey and state Attorney General Jack Conway   had been pursuing additional indictments against Farmer when the plea bargain was reached.<ref name=guiltyplea /> Although still restricted from leaving the state, Farmer was allowed to remain free pending sentencing.<ref name=pleaterms />

Van Tatenhove sentenced Farmer to 27 months in federal prison on January 14, 2014.<ref name=sentence>{{cite news |last=Kocher |first=Greg |title=Farmer Sentenced to 27 Months in Prison &ndash; Ex-UK Star, Ag Commissioner Must Also Pay $120K in Restitution |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=January 15, 2014 |page=A1}}</ref> He recommended that the sentence be served at the [[Federal Correctional Institution, Manchester|Federal Correctional Institution in Manchester]], Farmer's hometown, but the [[Federal Bureau of Prisons]] opted to assign him to the [[United States Penitentiary, Hazelton]] near [[Bruceton Mills, West Virginia]].<ref name=sentence /><ref name=prisonassign>{{cite news |title=Farmer Assigned to Prison Camp |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 14, 2014 |page=A3}}</ref> The ''Lexington Herald-Leader'' noted that Farmer's inmate number, 16226-032, was reminiscent of his college jersey number, 32.<ref name=number32>{{cite news |title=Farmer Will Get to be '32' in Prison, Too |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=January 28, 2014 |page=A5}}</ref>

Originally scheduled to report to prison on March 18, Farmer was granted a one-week delay by Van Tatenhove to watch his son, Trey, play for Clay County High School in the KHSAA basketball tournament.<ref name=reportdelay>{{cite news |title=Judge Delays Farmer's Prison Report Date |newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader |date=March 15, 2014 |page=A3}}</ref> Van Tatenhove insisted that he granted the delay in deference to the Farmer family, not as a special favor for Farmer himself.<ref name=reportdelay /> On March 25, 2014, Farmer reported to the satellite camp of the Hazelton prison to begin serving his sentence.<ref name=prisonreport>{{cite web |title=Farmer reports to federal prison to begin 27-month sentence |publisher=WKYT |location=[[Lexington, Kentucky]] |date=March 25, 2014 |url=http://www.wkyt.com/home/headlines/Farmer-reports-to-federal-prison-to-begin-27-month-sentence-252324081.html |accessdate=October 13, 2014}}</ref>

